<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Cotton Output Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Cotton Growers
Association (CGA) Thursday said cotton production for the just
ended season was down by between 15 and 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
CGA chief executive Doug Pascoe told the Zimbabwe News Agency
that picking was almost complete and a survey of all regions
showed that yields were not as expected.
</P>
<P>
He said the symposium to be held on August 6 in Harare would
attempt to identify the reasons for the disappointing yields this
season, adding the exact reasons for the fall in yields would be
dealt with in detail.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, which in a good season produces an average 270,000
tons of seed cotton, is regarded as the largest producer in the
region, earning about three billion Zimbabwean Dollars (170
million U.S. Dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Pascoe said final statistics on the season's production were
not yet out, but output would be less than last year's 270,000
tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
