<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Government to Pay Billions for Pay-Equity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian federal government has
underpaid nearly 200,000 current and former employees for the past
13 years, the Canadian Human Rights Tribunal ruled in a judgement
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In return, the tribunal has ordered the government to pay at
least 3 billion Canadian dollars for the pay-equity bill.
</P>
<P>
Even at a low estimate, the decision would mean the workers,
mostly clerks and secretaries making less than 30,000 Canadian
dollars (20,429 U.S. dollars) a year, could get 13 years of back
pay amounting to an average of 15,000 Canadian dollars (10,210
U.S. dollars) for each person.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of workers who will receive the money are
women.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal said the underpayment by the government to female
workers, compared with their male counterparts for the past 13
years, violates the 1978 Canadian Human Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
The government has 30 days to appeal the tribunal's ruling to
the federal Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
