<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Calls for Fight Against Gender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The signing of international
conventions deploring violence against women has not achieved its
intended purpose, the United Nations Fund for Women Regional
Director for Southern Africa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gita Welch said many African governments had ratified
international conventions such as the African Charter on Human
Rights, but very little had been done on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Zimbabwe Women's Human Rights Tribunal, Welch
said, ''the rights of women and children are still being denied
50 years after the signing of the universal declaration of human
rights.''
</P>
<P>
She said it was against this background that U.N. Fund for
Women launched a campaign on the elimination of violence against
women in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government would be lobbied to implement all
its policies against gender violence as a matter of priority.
</P>
<P>
Welch said more pressure groups should be formed to counter
some conservative traditions and religious fundamentalists
violating human rights.
</P>
<P>
The one-day tribunal was organized by Zimbabwe Women's
Resource Center and network to celebrate the 50th anniversary of
the universal declaration of human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
