<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's Parliament Sets Date for Early Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish parliament Saturday
overwhelmingly approved April 18, 1999, as the date for holding
early elections one year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
In a vote of 448-12, the parliament also decided that the 21st
parliamentary general elections and the provincial elections will
be held simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the date of the elections was changed from
the originally proposed April 25 because the National Sovereignty
and Children Festival will be held on April 23.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, who is leader of
Motherland Party, bridged his gaps with two partners, Democratic
Left Party leader Bulent Ecevit and Democratic Turkey Party leader
Husamettin Cindoruk, by reaching agreement to hold the elections
on April 25 of next year.
</P>
<P>
Before the agreement, Ecevit had insisted that the elections
should be held in November or December of this year, while
Cindoruk requested that the elections be held later than April
1999.
</P>
<P>
Having reached consensus with Republican People's Party leader
Deniz Baykal, who supports Yilmaz's minority coalition despite
being in the opposition, Yilmaz decided to hold the elections in
April 1999.
</P>
<P>
At Baykal's request, Yilmaz's coalition is expected to resign
at the end of this year and a "low profile election government"
will be formed to handle the state affairs during the transition
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
