<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1630 GMT, July 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A European Union (EU) envoy Thursday met
separately with the Israeli prime minister and Palestinian chief
negotiator to brief them on his latest shuttle diplomacy in
Israel, Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Angel Moratinos, EU special envoy to the Middle East,
told Benjamin Netanyahu about Syrian and Lebanese positions on
Israel's offer of withdrawal from south Lebanon and the resumption
of Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
But according to the Prime Minister's Office, nothing special
has come out from the briefing. (Israel-Palestine-EU Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Eight people were charred to death when an
Alliance Air Dornier aircraft caught fire and crashed onto an
aircraft components repair shed at the naval airport in the port
city of Kochi in the far Southwest of India Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that besides the three crew members
and three passengers including a pregnant woman, two workers in
the shed were also killed in the crash while five others were
injured.
</P>
<P>
The 18-seater aircraft caught fire within seconds after it took
off. All the victims died on the spot and their bodies were
charred beyond recognition, police said. (India-Plane Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SIEMREAP, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Incumbent Co-Premier Hun Sen,
appearing set to become Cambodia's next prime minister, met with
King Sihanouk here Thursday and indicated he got the monarch's
acknowledgement of his plan to form a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen told reporters after the meeting that "the king was
pleased with the idea of forming a coalition government with Hun
Sen as the prime minister and officials of his ruling Cambodian
People's Party (CPP) controlling five important ministries.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said he told the king that the next government would
apply the system of one prime minister to replace the two-prime
minister system being practiced now. (Cambodia-Hun Sen-King)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- New Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi formed a
so-called "economic reconstruction" cabinet Thursday by appointing
former Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa as finance minister in a bid
to revive the ailing Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet lineup also features well-known author and one-time
trade official Taichi Sakaiya as head of the Economic Planning
Agency, former University of Tokyo President Akito Arima as
education minister, and a 37-year-old political rookie, Seiko
Noda, as posts and communications minister.
</P>
<P>
Noda, a two-term House of Representatives member and the only
woman in the 21-member cabinet, is the youngest politician to
occupy a cabinet post in Japan since the end of World War II.
(Japan-New Cabinet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party president
Keizo Obuchi was elected Prime Minister by Parliament Thursday
despite dissent from the Upper House.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 61, was named Prime Minister by the Lower House,
polling 268 of 494 valid votes in the LDP-controlled Lower House.
(Japan-Obuchi-PM) 
</P>
