<HEADLINE> Urgent: Iraq Rages at U.S. Position on Nuclear File </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 30 (Xinhua)-- Iraq on Thursday condemned the
U.S. for its "arbitrary and aggressive" position that prevented
the U.N. Security Council from taking a "just and fair" position
on Iraq's nuclear file.
</P>
<P>
The condemnation was included in a statement issued after the
joint meeting of Iraq's Revolutionary Command Council and the
ruling Baath Party, which was chaired by President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency reported that the joint meeting was
convened after the Security Council failed to reach an agreement
Wednesday on Iraqi nuclear weapons inspection after reviewing a
report by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
</P>
<P>
China, Russia and France proposed that Iraq's nuclear file
should be closed, and the inspection be shifted to the long-term
monitoring from the present intrusive monitoring.
</P>
<P>
But the United States and Britain were opposed to any actions
taken by the the Security Council to scale back the nuclear
inspection on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi statement said that "the way of dealing with
(Iraq's) nuclear file... gives a flagrant example of the
arbitrary dealing with Iraq's legitimate issue."
</P>
<P>
"All the IAEA reports... have shown that its tasks have
been fulfilled, and that it has actually been exercising only
monitoring and verification activities," says the statement.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the statement criticized the U.N. Special
Commission for disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM, for working for the
benefit of the American scheme by deliberately prolonging its
mission in Iraq and the U.N. sanctions as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
