<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests U.N. Envoy's Meeting in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said Thursday that it has
lodged a protest to the U.N. against U.N. Resident Representative
in Cyprus Ann Hercus' meeting with a senior official of the
self-proclaimed Turkish Cypriot regime in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides said at his daily
press briefing here that the Cypriot government pointed out to the
U.N. that meetings the U.N. envoy holds with the two sides in
Cyprus "should always be in line with the U.N. Security Council
resolutions on the Cyprus issue."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman disclosed that the U.N. response was that the
recent meeting that Hercus held with the so-called foreign
minister of the northern Cypriot regime "does not in any way
constitute recognition of the illegal entity unilaterally declared
in the Turkish-occupied areas."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has called upon all states "not to
recognize the purported state of the 'Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus' set by secessionist acts" and "not to facilitate
or in any way assist the aforesaid secessionist entity,"
Stylianides added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Greece coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally a breakaway entity
in 1983, which was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ann Hercus came to Cyprus early this month to replace his
predecessor Feissel, who retired after 15-year service in Cyprus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Scholar Stresses Importance of Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan scholar Thursday
stressed the importance of trade to attain sustainable growth,
saying it is essentially fundamental to put in place various
liberalization measures to this end.
</P>
<P>
In a presentation on ''Trade and Growth in Sub-Saharan Africa
(SSA)'' at the U.N. Conference Center here, Njuguna Ndungu said,
''evidence has shown that developing countries which have
successfully achieved high sustained growth have also taken
advantage of trade opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
He stated that ''SSA countries have shifted more to outward
orientation through trade liberalization with encouraging results
in 1995 and 1996.''
</P>
<P>
According to him, export growth for the African region in the
1995-96 period has accelerated and export earnings grew on
average at 8 percent during the two years.
</P>
<P>
''This perhaps marks the start of rewards from policy reforms
to growth and thus break the vicious circle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Ndungu believed the importance of enhancing policies on export
and overall growth, and said, ''but a more prominent role is
played by macro-economic policies; the prominent ones are
exchange rate policies, reduction in exchange controls and price
stability.''
</P>
<P>
''A major drawback in strengthening the virtuous circle from
reforms to growth and export performance is the debt service
burden which crowds out domestic expenditures needed for
supporting expansion of productive capacity and infrastructure
for growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
''Another bottleneck is the underdeveloped state of human
capacity which stifles absorption of technological competence
availed through interaction of openness and foreign direct
investment,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
Referring to global trade in sub-Saharan Africa, he said the
African share in global trade has dropped from 3 percent in 1950s
to one percent in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the SSA's ''increasingly marginalized in world
trade'' to the fact that ''Africa does not trade enough - trade
shares are low'' and ''trade policy is much to blame for this
outcome.''
</P>
<P>
The two-hour lecture was organized by the economic and social
policy division of the United Nations Economic Commission for
Africa (ECA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
