<HEADLINE> BMW to Build New Rolls-Royce Model in 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 30 (Xinhua) -- German carmaker BMW said Thursday it
would build a new Rolls-Royce model at a planned new plant in
England as of the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Munich-based company said: "As of the year
2003 a new Rolls-Royce model will be launched on the market."
</P>
<P>
The new plant, he added, would be "an exclusive production site
for high-tech vehicles."
</P>
<P>
The recently-launched Rolls-Royce model, the Silver Seraph,
would also be produced at the new plant since 2003, according to
him.
</P>
<P>
But the main bodywork of the cars would continue to be
manufactured at the Rolls-Royce plant in Crewe, England, which
would be taken over by German carmaker Volkswagen (VW).
</P>
<P>
BMW was outbid by VW in purchasing British luxery carmaker
Rolls-Royce weeks ago. But under a latest deal, it will pay 40
million pounds for the rights to the Rolls-Royce name as of 2003,
compared to the 340 million pounds it offered in bidding.
</P>
<P>
According to the deal, VW will surrender the rights to the
Rolls-Royce name as of 2003 and be left with the rights to the
name and production of the Bentley versions of Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
VW should also rename the Rolls-Royce headquarters in Crewe as
Bentley Motor Cars Ltd, while BMW will set up a new subsidiary,
which will carry the traditional name Rolls-Royce Motor Cars.
</P>
<P>
Rolls-Royce had been insisting on awarding the name only to
BMW, which has long been producer of Rolls-Royce engines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
