<HEADLINE> Ireland Completes Final Procedure on Ratifying EU Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Ireland has
completed the final procedure on ratifying the European Union's
(EU) Amsterdam Treaty by handing over the formal document to the
Italian government.
</P>
<P>
Irish ambassador to Rome Joseph Small Thursday handed over the
instrument of ratification, signed by Irish President Mary
McAleese, to the Italian authorities who regulate such matters,
press reports from Dublin said.
</P>
<P>
Irish Foreign Minister David Andrews said in a statement issued
in Dublin: "As the perspective of enlargement of the Union draws
nearer, the Treaty of Amsterdam will better equip the European
Union to meet the challenges ahead."
</P>
<P>
Irish voters approved the Amsterdam Treaty with a 61.7 percent
majority in a national referendum held in May, committing the
country to closer cooperation on issues such as crime, employment,
and foreign and security policy within the 15-nation EU bloc.
</P>
<P>
The new EU treaty comes into effect on the first day of the
second month after the last country formally ratifies it, the
Irish government said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Germany, Sweden, Denmark, Britain, Finland
and Austria had ratified the treaty while the rest are expected to
complete the procedure by early 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
