<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Azerbaijan to Agree on Delimitation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 30 (Xinhua) -- In a joint statement circulated on
Thursday Russia and Azerbaijan said that they intend to sign an
agreement on the delimitation of the Caspian Seabed, according to
the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement was issued following talks between the
Russian delegation headed by First Deputy Foreign Minister Boris
Pastukhov, who arrived in Baku on Tuesday, and the Azerbaijani
delegation headed by Foreign Minister Tofik Zulfugarov.
</P>
<P>
The statement says both Russia and Azerbaijan are confident
that "all problems pertaining to the status of the Caspian Sea
will be based on the consensus of all Caspian states".
</P>
<P>
The sides exchanged views on the utilization of the water and
bed of the Caspian Sea, and analyzed two options: joint use of the
water and the division of the seabed on the one hand, or the
division of the water and seabed into national sectors, on the
other, the document reads.
</P>
<P>
The two countries stated that before the definition of the new
legal status of the Caspian Sea, the agreements between the Russian
Federation and Persia of February 26,1921, and the agreement on
trade and navigation between the USSR and Iran of March 25, 1940,
should remain in force, including the long-established practice of
navigation, fishing and border protection.
</P>
<P>
They have confirmed that the Caspian Sea should be divided into
sectors by agreement with corresponding neighboring and opposite
states along the median line, modified on the basis of the
principles of fairness and mutual agreement and with due account
taken of the islands, geological features, and other factors.
</P>
<P>
The two sides emphasized that the ecological system of the
Caspian Sea and of its components must be preserved and protected,
and the Caspian states should sign an agreement on the biological
resources as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
