<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IGC Estimates World Wheat Supply and Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) - Despite revisions to estimates for a
number of countries, world wheat production is forecast just 1 m.
Tons lower than last month at 597 m. tons, compared with the
record 610 m tons. in 1997, International Grains Council announced
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The main changes include higher figures for the EC, the United
States, Turkey, and Australia, and reductions for Argentina,
Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
On the world wheat trade, IGC said the total number is 1 m.
tons higher at 95m. tons, but still 1 m. lower than last season.
</P>
<P>
The overall decline reflects the reduced level of commercial
imports into South Asia, especially Pakistan, the stagnation in
demand in Pacific Asia and the recovery in domestic crops in North
Africa, according to IGC.
</P>
<P>
The increase from last month is attributable to the
announcement that the US government will purchase wheat for
donation to food deficit countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
World wheat consumption is forecast at 601 m. tons, 13 m. more
than in 1997/98. Weakening prices compared with other grains,
especially maize will boost feed use in both the EC and the US,
IGC estimated.
</P>
<P>
The figure for world wheat stocks is now 2 m. lower at 127 m.
tons. Smaller harvests mean that stocks are likely to be drawn
down in China, India and Russia, IGC said.
</P>
<P>
However, those in the five major exporters are forecast to rise
by an aggregate 7 m. to 48m. tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
