<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People in UK Are Losing Houses, Says CML </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) - Home repossessions in Britain
increased in the first six months of this year for the first time
since 1995, according to the latest figures released by the
Council of Mortgage Lenders (CML).
</P>
<P>
The 10 percent jump in the number of repossessions to 17310 in
the second half of 1997 means that more than 600 people a week are
losing their homes.
</P>
<P>
The announcement coincided with the release of figures from the
Lord Chancellor's department showing repossession actions up 18
percent on this time last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the housing sector blamed the rises on several
factors including interest rate rises, the reduction in mortgage
interest tax relief, cuts in income support and a rise in marriage
break-ups.
</P>
<P>
Further gloom for home-owners came from Nationwide Building
Society's quarterly house price survey, which showed a slowdown in
the housing market in the second quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to expectations, market activity faltered in the
first half of 1998," Nationwide, one of the biggest building
societies in Britain, said, citing sales figures 6 percent lower
than last year.
</P>
<P>
The CML and the housing charity Shelter were reported to lobby
for improved protection for mortgage borrowers to ward off the
threat of repossession.
</P>
<P>
Shelter wants to see mortgage insurance, also known as
accident, sickness and unemployment policies, to be compulsory.
</P>
<P>
"I agree that the cost might put a few people off taking out a
mortgage, but that is a small price to pay to prevent the
devastation that repossession can cause," said Chris Holmes,
director of Shelter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
