<HEADLINE> Mogadishu to Form Security Force at Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Committee for the
Business Community issued a statement here Thursday, calling for
the formation of an armed force to improve security around
markets in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Banditry activities are increasing day by day in the Somali
capital, ns lots of killings, abduction and armed robberies,
mainly against the minority individuals, have overshadowed the
area surrounding Mogadishu's main markets.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to this, the Supreme Committee for the Business
Community, the main telecommunications companies of Olympic and
Al-Barakat as well as the money transfer dealers of Sundus,
Dahabshil and Al-Wakil plus other interested emporium owners have
been meeting to find ways to cope with the increasing insecurity
especially around the main market of Bakara since mid July.
</P>
<P>
The committee has concluded that 100 strong and well-armed men
with four military officials should be recruited to guard the
security around the Bakara market.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the security members to be
recruited should be healthy, aged between 25 and 40 with no habit
of smoking, khat chewing or alcoholic drinking, bring along with
his own gun and recommended by a known businessman.
</P>
<P>
Once he was dead or injured during operations, the committee
will compensate the family for the victims, while all other
damages caused by the market's security personnel against
innocent civilians will also be dealt with by the Bakara market
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Each of the 100 armed men will be given 15,000 Somali
Shillings or two U.S. Dollars per day while each of the four
commanding officials will be given 20,000 Shillings or 2.5 U.S.
Dollars everyday.
</P>
<P>
With four temporary telephone sets to facilitate
communications they will be divided into five groups in the five
main posts in Bakara market.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Mohamed Ali Absiyeh from Al-Barakat Telecommunications
would be the general commander of this force.
</P>
<P>
The call for the formation of this force coincided with the
meeting of Mogadishu's main faction leaders including Ali Mahdi,
Hussein Mohamed Aidid and Osman Ali Atto with Hussein Hajji Bod,
the new rival of Ali Mahdi Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which took place in Bod's residence is aimed at
resolving the difference between Ali Mahdi and Bod over the
formation of an administration for Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
