<HEADLINE> Mubarak "Pessimistic" over Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Thursday said he began to feel pessimistic about the peace process
for the first time in many years.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is not satisfactory at all," Mubarak said, "I am
not optimistic, as I used to be."
</P>
<P>
He said he had maintained an optimistic attitude and actively
involved in the mediation efforts, despite up and downs in the
peace march initiated by former Egyptian President Anwar Sadat
nearly two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
But the president now sounded alarm against the danger of a
collapse of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He told members of the Arab Journalists Union in the
Mediterranean city of Alexandria that the Middle East issue is
becoming more complicated.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock in Palestinian-Israeli talks has run into its 16th
month and recent direct talks have so far failed to produce an
agreement on a further Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak warned against exercising pressures on Palestinians,
pointing out that the Israeli hardline stance will not force
peoples to give up their rights.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian people will not accept aggression on their
lands and the Lebanese will never accept the occupation of their
territories," he added.
</P>
<P>
But he advised against jumping to conclusions.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody can predict what will befall the peace process until
it comes to an end," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the Egyptian-French initiative on reviving the
peace process through holding an international peace conference,
saying it does not "alienate" the U.S. role but rather
"complements" it.
</P>
<P>
"The announcement of the initiative followed Egyptian and
French contacts with the U.S. administration," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is working to turn the proposal into a plan in case that
the U.S. mediation fails.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks were stalled after Israel began
construction of a new settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in March
1997.
</P>
<P>
Egypt signed a treaty with Israel in 1979, becoming the first
Arab country to achieve peace with the Jewish state, which had
fought four wars with the Arabs since its creation in 1948.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
