<HEADLINE> Makerere to Admit 8,000 Private Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's number one university,
Makerere University, will admit 8,000 private students in the
coming academic year, four times the number taken under
government sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
A clerk in the Academic Registrar's Office told Xinhua
Thursday that the increasing enrolment of private students is in
response to a cut in the university's budget by the government.
But he did not mention the size of the budget cut.
</P>
<P>
The private students are to be registered in certificate,
diploma and degree courses, he added.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the private students have to live off campus
because the university's accommodating capacity is relatively
small. But most of the 2,000 government financed students are
offered accommodations on campus.
</P>
<P>
This year, although there are 15,630 students qualified to
join Makerere, financial constraints and facilities cannot allow,
he said. Some 8,277 places have been advertized in the various
courses.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1922, Makerere University is one of the oldest
and most famous universities on the Africandations continent. It
used to enjoy close relations with the University of London when
Uganda was under British rule.
</P>
<P>
With nine faculties, four schools and six institutes, the
institution of higher learning has 3,300 posts for academic,
administrative and support staff and some 20,000 registered
students.
</P>
<P>
It has exchange programs with many famous universities around
the globe and takes students from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
It has also been a cradle from which many famous people step
onto their respective ways to success. Former Tanzanian President
Julius Nyerere and the country's current President Benjamin
William Mkapa are both graduates of this university. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
