<HEADLINE> 1stld: Iraq Leadership Calls for National Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 30 (Xinhua) -- As the hope for a speedy lifting
of U.N. sanctions diminishes, Iraqi leadership said Thursday it
will hold a national debate soon to discuss the critical situation
facing the nation.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at Thursday's joint meeting of Iraq's
Revolutionary Command Council and the ruling Baath Party, which was
chaired by President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after the meeting condemned the United
States for its "arbitrary and aggressive" position that prevented
the United Nations Security Council from taking a "just and fair"
position on Iraq's nuclear file.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the national debate would be "discussing the
position and measures that should be taken to protect the supreme
interests of our people, and the security and sovereignty of the
homeland."
</P>
<P>
It added the Iraqi leadership would urge its people to support
its decision "which will result from the subsequent circumstances
and discussions."
</P>
<P>
This call was believed to be a threat that the Iraqi leadership
might return to the collision course with the U.N. over the
prolonged inspection mission on its weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
The joint meeting was convened after the U.N. Security Council
failed to reach an agreement Wednesday on Iraq's nuclear weapons
program after reviewing a report presented by the International
Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
Russia, France and China believed that the nuclear inspection
mission in Iraq should be shifted to long-term monitoring from the
present intrusive monitoring.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. and Britain were opposed to any actions by the
Security Council to scale back the nuclear inspection at this
stage.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership's statement denounced the council's way of
dealing with its nuclear file as "a flagrant example of the
arbitrary in dealing with Iraq's legitimate issue."
</P>
<P>
It also attacked the U.N. Special Commission for disarmament in
Iraq, or UNSCOM, for working for the U.S. benefit by deliberately
prolonging its inspection as well as the crippling U.N. sanctions
imposed since Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The lifting of the U.N. sanctions hinges on the UNSCOM's report
on its inspection mission in Iraq which is to be presented to the
Security Council in October this year.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the UNSCOM was in fact fully aware that all
the requirements on disarmament had been fully fulfilled by Iraq
several years ago because all the weapons, factories and
equipments were already destroyed.
</P>
<P>
On the scheduled visit to Iraq by UNSCOM Chairman Richard
Butler on August 3, it warned him against continuing his "well
known methods of manoevering, misleading, arousing marginal issues
and prolonging its work indefinitely for the benefit of the
American criminal scheme." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
