<HEADLINE> Russia Places Ban on Nazi Symbols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A draft law banning all Nazi
symbols, literature and videos was approved by the Russian
government on Thursday, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the banning law, Russian Justice Minister Pavel
Krasheninnikov stressed that the law will come up with explicit
regulations in that field, "and it will be a ban on the symbols of
the Italian national-working party and the German
national-socialist party."
</P>
<P>
The minister said the ban will spread to video and audio
production, except for the cases when those symbols are used in
films and literature advocating humanitarian ideas and denouncing
fascism.
</P>
<P>
The idea of the draft law was hailed by Russian Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko, who noted that the law must be introduced in the
State Duma as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass cited Kiriyenko as reporting that most of the
deputies support the project, and that such a bill is the most
civilized way of fighting fascism and neo-fascism in Russia.
