<HEADLINE> Palestinians See Hope for Early Israeli Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian diplomat said
here Thursday that Israeli opposition's latest victory in a
parliamentary vote on early elections might give a chance to the
stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mohamad Sobeih, Palestinian chief delegate to the Arab League,
told reporters that this move has demonstrated that the Israeli
government is lacking credibility among the Israeli public due to
its anti-peace approach.
</P>
<P>
Israeli opposition parties Wednesday won the preliminary
approval of a bill calling for dissolution of the Knesset
(Parliament) and early elections, a move seen as a blow to Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
But for before becoming a law, the bill should go through three
more parliamentary votes that many expected it to fail to pass. A
majority of 61 votes in the 120-seat Knesset will be needed to
pass such a bill.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih said the voting results reflected a division among
Israelis as to where the incumbent government is taking them
because Netanyahu's intransigent policies threaten to return the
region to the cycle of tensions and violence.
</P>
<P>
"A large percentage of the Israeli people want peace and need
the support of several parties, especially the U.S.," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has proposed that Israel withdraw from
another 13.1 percent of the West Bank in exchange for more efforts
by the Palestinian side to crack down on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
While the Palestinians have accepted the proposal, Netanyahu
has refused to do so citing security concerns. The direct talks
that were resumed on July 19 quickly broke down due to the Israeli
intransigence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
