<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes European Court Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus on Thursday welcomed a
European court ruling ordering Turkey to compensate a Greek
Cypriot woman for property deprivation.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides told a press
briefing that the court decision will help find "a just, correct,
viable and workable solution to the Cyprus problem."
</P>
<P>
The European Court of Human Rights Tuesday ordered Turkey to
pay nearly 900,000 U.S. dollars in compensation to Titina Loizidou
for her properties in Kyrenia, in the north of the divided
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Loizidou, a Greek Cypriot who fled Kyrenia in 1974 when Turkey
landed troops there, began the legal battle in 1989 over her right
to the properties in now self-declared Turkish Cypriot state,
recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The decision of the Strasbourg-based court "confirms that
Turkey is an occupation force in Cyprus," Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
"It is responsible for the violation of the right to property
and for depriving the right of freedom of movement, access and
enjoyment of property," he added.
</P>
<P>
Observers here sees the court decision as "setting a legal
precedent" that may open the way for more claims of properties
against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has rejected the decision, saying it lacks "the means of
applicability and implementation."
</P>
<P>
Some 180,000 Greek Cypriots escaped or expelled following the
Turkish intervention in 1974 in the wake of a failed coup by the
Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has more than 35,000 troops in the north with the
claimed aim of protecting the Turkish ethnic minority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
