<HEADLINE> Tanzania Unhappy About Foreign Interference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian foreign minister
has voiced dissatisfaction with the foreign countries which had
meddled in the country's internal affairs, saying his government
will take measures against it.
</P>
<P>
Without specifying the countries, Jakaya Kikwete, the Minister
of Foreign Affairs and International Co-operation, said the
government has grown aware that some resident envoys "are poking
noses into the country's internal affairs," media reports said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete, who was tabling the 1998/99 budget estimates
Wednesday for his ministry at the National Assembly in the
central city of Dodoma, said these countries have severely
violated diplomatic norms and the Tanzanian government will not
"condone the trend."
</P>
<P>
The government is considering how best to handle the
situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister asserted that Tanzania would prefer
poverty in freedom to wealthiness in slavery.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete also renewed the country's commitment to regional
blocs like East African Co-operation (EAC), Kagera Basin
Organization, Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa, and
Southern Africa Development Community.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania is working closely with Kenya and Uganda, the
other two members of EAC, in defense, security,
telecommunications, road and transportation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said Tanzania will further cooperate with
other members of the Non-Aligned Movement, the Organization of
African Unity, the Group 77 and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Also on the occasion, Kikwete requested parliament to
endorse a budget of 13.06 billion Shillings (about 19.4 million
U.S. Dollars) for his ministry.  
</P>
