<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Breast Cancer Deaths Reduced With High-Dose </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian study has shown that a
specific high-dose chemotherapy compared to standard chemotherapy
can further reduce deaths by 19 percent in pre-menopausal women
with breast cancer that has spread to the lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that the same chemotherapy drugs can
reduce the risk of breast cancer recurrence by 29 percent,
according to a news release issued Thursday by the Canadian Cancer
Society.
</P>
<P>
The findings are published in the August, 1998 issue of the
Journal of Clinical Oncology.
</P>
<P>
The study was supported by the National Cancer Institute of
Canada Clinical Trials Group, with funds from the Canadian Cancer
Society, and Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Inc.
</P>
<P>
The clinical trial took place in 36 centres across Canada and
followed for at least five years all 710 participating women, who
were pre-menopausal and diagnosed with Stage II breast cancer:
cancer that has invaded the lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
In the study, 359 women were randomly assigned to the standard
chemotherapy regimen of cyclophosphamide, methotrexate and
fluorouracil (CMF) and 351 women received the high-dose
chemotherapy regime of cyclophosphamide, epirubicin and
fluorouracil (CEF).
</P>
<P>
In the CMF group, 107 patients died compared with 85 patients
in the CEF group, and 169 patients developed recurrence of their
breast cancer compared with 132 CEF patients.
</P>
<P>
"Both relapse-free and overall survival were improved in women
who received CEF compared with CMF, with a 29 percent risk
reduction in recurrent breast cancer and a 19 percent reduction in
mortality," the study concluded.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that there were more side effects such as
hair loss, nausea and a small increased risk of leukemia
associated with CEF therapy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
