<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Defense Minister Ali
Shamkhani vowed Thursday to continue efforts to strengthen its
defense capability despite the U.S. pressure over its missile
development program.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a program on the state-run television, Shamkhani
said Iran's defense policy was to produce weapons according to its
needs and it would continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
The minister's remarks came after U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Tuesday signed an executive order to impose sanctions on seven
Russian firms and institutions for providing Iran with missile
technology.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Shamkhani confirmed the test of the Shahab-3
missile with a range of 1,300 kilometers on July 22 after
U.S. intelligence reports revealed the secret.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the U.S. allegation that Russia had transferred
missile technology to Iran, Shamkhani said the Shahab-3 missile
was produced by Iranian experts who have the capability of
producing surface-to-surface, surface-to-air and other kinds of
missiles.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister stressed that the balance of defense
capability was the only factor to maintain peace and stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iran could not abandon its present defense policy
as long as Israel, Iran's archrival, spares no efforts to
stockpile weapons.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating that Iran's policy was aimed at reducing tensions,
he voiced Tehran's readiness to expand security cooperation with
regional countries. 
</P>
