<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, U.S. Agree on Closer Defense Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Australia and the United States
said here Friday they would strengthen their military ties, such
as facilitating Australia's access to some U.S. technologies
important to the effectiveness of the Australian armed forces, and
intelligence collection.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique released here Friday by U.S. and
Australian foreign and defense ministers, both sides described
their defense cooperation under the alliance as "vibrant and
forward-looking."
</P>
<P>
"Australia also made it clear that it would continue to support
this U.S. posture (U.S. alliance ties with Japan, South Korea,
Australia and the forward deployment of the U.S. forces) in
practical ways, including through access to Australian ports and
airfields and providing areas for joint and unilateral training,
exercises, and tests of new capabilities."
</P>
<P>
The ministers, including U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Defense Secretary William Cohen and their Australian
counterparts Alexander Downer and Ian McLachlan, expressed
"satisfaction with the progress being made on developing training
areas in Northern Australia to allow large-scale exercises by U.S.
ground forces."
</P>
<P>
"Ministers also agreed to simply the procedures for providing
diplomatic clearance for visiting naval vessels to reflect the
importance of ship visits to the relationship."
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Friday, Australian Defense
Minister Ian McLachlan announced that his talks with U.S. foreign
and defense ministers produced a number of valuable outcomes for
the Australian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Among the outcomes is an agreement to further develop the
ability of the Australian and U.S. armed forces to operate
together, which includes steps to take advantage of the
far-reaching technology changes resulting from the information
revolution, and developing more effective planning on how
Australian and U.S. forces can operate together with this new
technology, McLachlan said.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to build a long-term partnership in the field
of wide-area surveillance, which involves projects such as
Airborne Early Warning and Control aircraft, and Operational Radar
Network.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized on the understanding of technology-sharing in
areas of central importance to the effectiveness of the Australian
armed forces and its capacity to contribute to coalition
operations, including submarines, Airborne Early Warning and
Control, and combat aircraft capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Australia has been modernizing its armed forces during the past
two years by introducing advanced weapons and equipment in a bid
to defend its vast land and territorial water and project its
power outside Australia.
</P>
<P>
The communique said both sides agreed on the centrality of the
"knowledge edge" to the successful conduct of military operations,
saying the ministers observed the intelligence was one critical
factor in the edge and that the two countries continued to enjoy a
particularly close and productive partnership in this area.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has set up powerful intelligence collecting facilities
in Australia, including the missile tracking facilities which
helped the American troops intercept missiles launched by Iraq
during the Gulf War in early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Australia also endorsed a program of cooperative
research in new capabilities for wide-area surveillance, a
proposal to establish a new committee to coordinate and promote
cooperation in equipment acquisition, technology and support, said
the communique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
