<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Related Death Toll in Bangladesh Rises to 242 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's flood-related death
toll has risen to 242, with 44 people killed in the current flood
overnight as gushing waters from the upstream made the situation
grave in the capital of Dhaka and other central districts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Most deaths were caused by drowning and boat-capsize while
other reasons included snake-bite, house collapse and diarrhea,
the national BSS news agency Friday quoted disaster management
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Buriganga and Turag rivers are flowing much above their
danger marks around Dhaka city, and they continue to rise,
according to the Flood Forecasting and Warning Center (FFWC).
</P>
<P>
The situation in five sub-districts of the capital and the
adjoining areas deteriorated "severely," the disaster management
officials said.
</P>
<P>
They added that 28,000 people of Dhaka were forced to take
refuge in 50 flood shelters while many others shifted to safe
places on their own.
</P>
<P>
Boats, instead of automobiles and rickshaws, took over the
streets in many low-lying areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains downpoured in Bangladesh in the past 20 days
already affecting over 17.5 million people in the 37 districts of
the total of 64.
</P>
<P>
Over 5,000 kilometers of roads, 1,722 kilometers of embankments
and 2,215 bridges and culverts have been damaged and about 200,00
hectares of crops washed away by the flood.
</P>
<P>
The present flood situation in the country is improving slowly,
with the situation having returned normal in 11 districts and
improved in nine districts. But the flood situation in Dhaka and
its adjoining areas as well as in Bangladesh's central districts
has turned for the worst, the FFWC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
