<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Test May Reduce Breast Cancer Surgeries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A new technique of telling apart
benign and cancerous lumps in the breast could save women from
unnecessary surgeries, doctors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
An international research, co-ordinated by the Imperial Cancer
Research Fund in the UK, has found that an equipment called the
Biofield Diagnostic System could reduce the number of biopsies
needed to diagnose breast cancer by more than half.
</P>
<P>
Developed by U.S. Biofield Corp, the non-invasive technique
measures electrical changes on the skin surface associated with
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
A study of 661 women published in The Lancet medical journal
showed it was effective in distinguishing the different types of
tumours.
</P>
<P>
The diagnosis of breast cancer usually needs physical
examination and biopsy to remove cells or tissues, which can be
time consuming and painful for women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
