<HEADLINE> Malaysia Insists Not to Relocate Railway Checkpoint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia insisted Friday that
it will not relocate its railway checkpoint with Singapore and
said it is up to Singapore to defuse the dispute over travel
procedures.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that there will be no problems (for railway
travelers) as it is well within Singapore's means and competence
not to create problems," Foreign Ministry Secretary-General Abdul
Kadir Mohamad said at a news conference here Friday on the eve of
the deadline set by Singapore for the relocation.
</P>
<P>
Singapore set August 1 as the deadline for Malaysia to relocate
its customs, immigration and quarantine formalities for rail
passengers from the Tanjong Pagar railway station in central
Singapore to Woodlands which is closer to the border with
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Kadir said "It is up to Singapore to decide whether the trains
will flow as usual. Of course they have the rights to do all the
checks."
</P>
<P>
A six-page statement, released by kadir at the press
conference, on the dispute and how talks between the two countries
to resolve it had broken down, said the dispute could be defused
if Singapore did not to carry out its decision to relocate the
checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysian Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar said
here Friday Malaysia and Singapore should settle their dispute
over the relocation of the checkpoint for railway passengers
without hurting the feelings of both sides.
</P>
<P>
The issue should be settled by returning to the negotiating
table, he told reporters here after opening an exhibition here,
according to the Malaysian national news agency Bernama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
