<HEADLINE> UK Ratifies Ottawa Convention on Banning Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The British government Friday
formally ratified the Ottawa Convention on banning landmines,
announcing a complete ban on all anti-personnel landmines by
British troops.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Office said in a joint statement with the
Ministry of Defense that Britain's instrument of ratification was
deposited with the United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan in
New York early Friday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary George Robertson said in the statement: "I am
today announcing that, even in extreme circumstances, any further
operational use of such mines by British forces will no longer be
allowed."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said: "We must dedicate
ourselves to removing the humanitarian threat posed by the
millions of mines already in the ground. Our goal is a world free
of anti-personnel landmines."
</P>
<P>
The final Parliamentary stages of the Landmines Bill were
completed in the House of Lords on July 24, enabling Britain to
become the 20th country to ratify the Ottawa Convention, calling
for an immediate ban on the use, production and transfer of
anti-personnel landmines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
