<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Unveils New Energy Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Friday announced a
new power policy to ensure cheap electricity generation through
indigenous resources, competitive bidding and minimum tariffs.
</P>
<P>
In a departure from the past policy, based on thermal, the new
policy envisages a proactive role for the government to promote
the use of indigenous coal and hydro-electric resources in power
generation, Minister for Water and Power Raja Nadir Pervez said at
a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan has 40,000 megawatt of hydel resources
which have remained untapped and coal reserves are estimated at
200 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
The new policy, he said, is based on exploitation of coal and
hydel reserves and conversion on gas wherever available also form
part of the policy.
</P>
<P>
The basis for private power project will be minimum levelized
tariff through international competitive bidding, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the policy, private power producers must implement
the project within the applicable tax laws of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The new policy provides for 90 percent First Year Allowance for
hydel power plant and power plants based on indigenous coal.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy, the companies are allowed to import plant and
 equipment on payment of customs duties, sales tax, food relief
and other surcharges as well as import licence fee.
</P>
<P>
The New policy also permits power generation companies to issue
corporate bonds, both bearer and registered. These companies are
also allowed to issue shares at discounted prices to enable
venture capital to be provided at higher rates of returns and
proportionate to the risk.
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks have been allowed to underwrite the issue of
shares and bonds by the private power companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
