<HEADLINE> Iranian Judiciary Chief Slams U.S. Sanctions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Iran's judiciary chief Ayatollah
Mohammad Yazdi Friday slammed the United States for imposing
sanctions on seven Russian companies alleged to have provided Iran
with missile technology.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Friday prayers congregation at Tehran
University, Yazdi said the instrument of threat was an out-of-date
ploy and trick and economic sanctions would boomerang on the U.S.
proper.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decided last Tuesday to bar government aid to and all
trade with seven Russian companies for their alleged transfer of
missile technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran conducted a successful test last Wednesday of the Shahab-3
missile with a range of 1,300 kilometers. The U.S. has voiced
concern about the test, because the missile could hit Saudi
Arabia, Israel or its forces stationed in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Iran has stressed that its missiles are only for defense
purpose and that the test was carried out by Iranian experts
"without any assistance from foreign countries."
</P>
<P>
Yazdi said that Washington made hue and cry over the missile
test in a bid to compensate for a political humiliation, referring
to a snub by Iran to an American overture last month for a
rapprochement between the two rivals.
</P>
<P>
He said the medium-ranged missile is a strategic weapon to
guarantee the defense of Iran against any possible threat, adding
that it is definitely not meant to threaten any country.
</P>
<P>
He accused the U.S. of holding double standards by showing
indifference toward Israel's weapons of mass destruction. He noted
that Washington is not even willing to make any reference to such
a looming and impending threat of Israel to the world, and the
region in particular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
