<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy Pauses for Second Month in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian economy paused for a
second consecutive month in May, edging down 0.2 percent from
April, Statistics Canada reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in over two years that the economy has
failed to grow for two consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
"Weakness in May fairly widespread, with the most significant
declines occurring in the finance, manufacturing, mining,
construction and transportation services industries," the
statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
The real estate industry advanced, while retailers and
wholesalers had a flat month, it added.
</P>
<P>
Canada's economy began to slow in late 1997 after putting in a
solid performance since the middle of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In May, the finance industries, which comprise banks, credit
unions and other financial institutions, fell 1.7 percent as
volume of share trade fell substantially.
</P>
<P>
Total manufacturing output dropped 0.3 percent in May, after a
0.9-percent slip in April.
</P>
<P>
Declines were recorded in 13 of 22 major industry groups,
accounting for about 60 percent of total manufacturing production,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Activity in the mining sector fell 1.4 percent in May, the
fourth decline in five months.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, construction fell 0.8 percent, and the
transportation, pipeline and storage industry declined 1.0 percent
in the month.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale sales decreased 1.0 percent, while real estate
services industry advanced 0.3 percent in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
