<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Diplomatic Expulsion Row Still Plagues Seoul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South Korea said here Friday that it
has discussed the issue with Russia on whether or not to allow an
expelled Russian diplomat to return to Seoul, which is apparently
different from an earlier statement.
</P>
<P>
During meetings between the foreign ministers of South Korea
and Russia in Manila, the Philippines, earlier this week, South
Korea agreed to consider the issue of allowing the expelled
diplomat to re-enter Seoul on humanitarian reasons, said Sun
Joun-yung, deputy minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
Sun's remarks are completely different from the announcement
made by a spokesman of the ministry Wednesday that South Korean
Foreign Minister Park Chung-soo and his Russian counterpart
Yevgeny Primakov did not discuss the issue when they met in Manila
during an ASEAN Regional Forum conference.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been pressing South Korea to allow expelled Oleg
Abramkin, councillor of the Russian Embassy to return to Seoul.
South Korea claimed Abramkin as a "persona non grata" and ordered
him to leave Seoul on July 8, in retaliation for Russia's
deportation of Cho Sung-woo, a councillor of the South Korean
Embassy in Moscow, on spy charges on July 4 this year.
</P>
<P>
On July 20, South Korea said it will reduce its diplomat number
in Russia by calling back five more diplomats under the demand of
the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
"Seoul will be able to settle the diplomatic issue with Russia
if it allows Abramkin to return to the Russian Embassy in Seoul,"
Valery Suhinin, minister-counsellor of the Russian Embassy in
Seoul, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Park denied media reports that South Korea has
agreed to permit the return of the Russian diplomat to Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Park made the denial after Primakov said South Korea had agreed
to allow Abramkin to return to the Russian Embassy in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
In Manila, Park and Primakov reportedly met two times to seek a
quick solution to the diplomatic row, that has soured their good
bilateral relations, which the two nations have enjoyed since the
establishment of diplomatic ties in 1990.
</P>
<P>
"Minister Park told Primakov he would consider allowing
Abramkin to return to Seoul for a temporary visit," said Cho
IL-whan, director general for European affairs of the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs and Trade, who was accompanying Park in Manila
during the ASEAN Regional Forum conference.
</P>
<P>
The director general also said when Park promised to consider
Abramkin's return, Primakov said such permission would make it
possible for Russia to allow more South Korean intelligence
officers with diplomatic status to be stationed in Russia.
</P>
<P>
However, after his meeting with Park Tuesday, Primakov said
Abramkin will go back to Seoul and stay there until his
replacement arrives in September this year, while Cho will not be
allowed to return to Moscow since "he was caught red-handed."
</P>
<P>
No clear explanation could prove why the two foreign ministers
made contradictory remarks on the alleged reinstatement of the
expelled Russian diplomat.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, it was inferred that Primakov was
either "telling a lie or disclosing a secret agreement" with his
South Korean counterpart on Abramkin's reinstatement, some people
said.
</P>
<P>
Media reports, which alleged that the two ministers have
already reached a secret agreement on Abramkin's return, said Park
must be held responsible for what is seen as a heavy blow to the
face of South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
South Korean opposition Grand National Party has accused the
Kim Dae-jung government of engaging in humiliating diplomacy,
which required Park to resign as foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Informed government officials said the expelled Russian
diplomat could be allowed to return to Seoul under the status of a
Russian citizen, not a diplomat.
</P>
<P>
However, media reports said the return of the expelled foreign
diplomat, regardless of what status he will have, would hurt the
nation's pride by reversing the decision it made earlier as a
sovereign state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
