<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asian Leaders Call for Cooperation in Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South Asian countries Friday
agreed to strengthen their cooperation in meeting the challenges
and opportunities resulting from the world's fast changing
economic environment, as manifested by globalization and the
financial turmoil in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the seven-member South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC), at their summit which ended here
Friday, discussed the impact of the current global economic
developments on the economies of Southeast Asian countries and
other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration adopted at the end of their three-day summit,
the leaders expressed serious concern over the severe distortions
produced by unrestrained globalization, as has been evidenced in
the downturn of the economies of several Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The financial turmoil flared up in Southeast Asia last July,
causing stock markets to plunge and regional currencies to devalue
sharply. Many economies in the region have contracted considerably
as a result of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
South Asia, one of the poorest regions in the world, has been
less affected by the financial and economic crisis in Southeast
Asia, but its leaders are showing no less concern at it.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar said last week
ahead of the summit that the crisis is happening so close to South
Asia that "it is a natural concern for all of us."
</P>
<P>
He said South Asian leaders would discuss the region's
"collective response towards global economic changes."
</P>
<P>
"The challenges and opportunities inherent in these fast
evolving developments," the Colombo Declaration said, "could best
be met and the full potential of South Asia realized through
effective, practical, regional and bilateral cooperation among
member states."
</P>
<P>
While reviewing the beneficial effects of globalization, the
leaders stressed that these crises are becoming unpredictable with
increased globalization, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
They expressed concern about the shortcomings of the existing
international monetary and financial system, and "its tardiness in
anticipating impending financial market crises sufficiently in
advance, so that pre-emptive remedial action be adopted," it said.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the problem would not be confined to Asia or
emerging economies, and that it can have global ramifications
unless more fundamental reforms are put in place.
</P>
<P>
They said that the individual financial systems of SAARC member
countries must be strengthened through enhancing institutional
capacity, surveillance mechanisms as well as through closer
consultations and coordination with regard to macro-economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed on the need for strengthened cooperation
among SAARC member countries to "identify, analyze and effectively
contend with the complex multi-faceted challenges inherent in the
global economic environment" that has been changing so radically
in the 1990s, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said they would sign a convention on combating the
crime against women and children in the region at their next
gathering in Kathmandu, Nepal in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said that they welcome the finalization of the
draft text on the Regional Convention on Combating the Crime of
Trafficking in Women and Children for Prostitution.
</P>
<P>
The leaders at their Colombo summit also decided that the
convention be broadened to cover other purposes of trafficking in
women and children other than prostitution, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
They also called for exploring the feasibility of establishing
a regional fund for rehabilitation of the victims of trafficking
in women and children on a voluntary basis.
</P>
<P>
The leaders decided to establish a South Asian Cultural Unity
to promote the distinctive arts of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was based on the rich, complex and varied
plurality of cultural and religious traditions.
</P>
<P>
The leaders pointed out that the SAARC process could draw more
deeply from the vitality and strength of South Asia's shared
cultural heritage as a source influencing and enhancing creative
energies in all fields.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said that their countries continue to face the
serious threat of terrorism in all its forms and manifestation and
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reiterated their firm commitment to combat these
activities in the region.
</P>
<P>
The leaders recalled the adoption of the 1996 U.N. Declaration
on Measures to Eliminate International Terrorism and urged all
member states to work towards its implementation.
</P>
<P>
They also called for international action to prevent the abuse
of refugee conventions and to halt activities which help
terrorist groups to collect funds for their activities in South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
The leaders pointed out that two SAARC conferences on
cooperation in police matters had been held since 1996. The first
conference was held in Sri Lanka in July, 1996. The second was
held last year in the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
They called for the continued sharing of expertise with regard
to the different areas of police investigation, and investigation
of organized crimes and drug related crimes.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reiterated their commitment to the eradication of
poverty in the region as early as possible, preferably by the year
2002.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized the need to encourage maximum participation by
target groups in the formulation and implementation of poverty
eradication programs.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also pointed out that Human Resource Development
was a key element in any poverty eradication program.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly they agreed that once the SAARC Center for Human
Resources Development was established in Islamabad it could look
into the possibility of its contributing to the strengthening of
the human
resources development components of the regional poverty
eradication
programs.
</P>
<P>
The leaders decided that discriminatory practices and
non-tariff barriers should be simultaneously removed on items in
respect of which tariff concessions are granted or have been
granted earlier.
</P>
<P>
Measures to remove structural impediments should also be taken
in order to move speedily towards the goal of the South Asian Free
Trade Area (SAFTA) which was agreed at the last summit in Male to
be established by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
SAARC launched the South Asian Preferential Trading Arrangement
(SAPTA) in December 1995 marking its first step towards the
creating of SAFTA.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reiterated the importance of achieving SAFTA and
towards achieving this, they decided to draft a comprehensive
treaty regime for creating a free trade area which will
incorporate binding time frames for freeing trade, measures to
facilitate trade and provisions to ensure equitable distribution
of benefits of trade to all states.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized the importance of finalizing the text or
regulatory framework by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the benefits of economic liberalization would
be more extensive through the promotion of trade creating joint
ventures, investment and trade in services such as tourism.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the seven member SAARC met in Colombo on July 29
to 31.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
