<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital's Blood Donation Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
Beijing Municipal People's Congress passed a Voluntary Blood
Donation Regulation today, which will take effect on October 1.
</P>
<P>
It will replace the city's blood donation regulations that
demand blood donations from healthy residents of a certain age and
is based on a national law, passed by the National People's
Congress Standing Committee in 1997, on voluntary blood donations.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 180,000 people in the Chinese capital donated blood,
compared with 130,000 in 1992, but these donations only cover half
of the city's yearly demand of 60 tons. The rest is covered by
bringing blood from other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The new rules institute a voluntary blood donation system and
say that the municipal and county governments should issue annual
donation quotas and the city government will give awards to anyone
who donates a total of 2,000 ml or more, and any unit that donates
20 percent more than the quota for five successive years.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, units that fail to live up to the quota will
be officially reprimanded by the city government.
</P>
<P>
And illegal sales of blood will mean forfeiture of any income
from the illicit trade and a fine of 100,000 yuan or more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
