<HEADLINE> Outgoing S. African Minister Mum on Sacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing South African
Correctional Services Minister Sipo Mzimela remained mum Friday
about his dismissal from the cabinet, South African Press
Association SAPA reported.
</P>
<P>
"The minister is today (Friday) still not commenting on the
matter until he discusses it with the president (Nelson
Mandela)... We are not sure when this meeting will take place,"
Mzimela's spokesman Bert Slabbert said.
</P>
<P>
Mzimela tendered his resignation in writing to Mandela
Wednesday after Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) leader Mangosuthu
Buthelezi blocked a desperate last-minute bid by the outgoing
minister to retain his cabinet post until the end of the current
parliamentary session.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of Mzimela, an IFP member, follows his
repeated clashes with his party over his calls for unity between
the IFP and the ruling African National Congress (ANC).
</P>
<P>
Mzimela first suggested an IFP-ANC merger at the end of last
year. In January the IFP's national council adopted a formal vote
of no confidence in Mzimela and earlier this month the party
removed him as its national deputy chairman.
</P>
<P>
It was still unclear whether MzimelapwHUX5%\
 IFP
member.
</P>
<P>
Other opposition parties welcomed the departure of Mzimela,
saying the controversial minister had failed to deliver on key
elements of prison management or to build the facilities needed
to house the growing prison population.
</P>
<P>
The National Party (NP) and the Democratic Party (DP)
criticized Mzimela for two mass releases of prisoners this year,
first of juveniles and second, earlier this month, the release of
9,000 prisoners to mark Mandela's birthday.
</P>
<P>
The more recent release has allegedly resulted in three
murders, a number of robberies and rapes.
</P>
<P>
The Freedom Front (FF) also slashed at Mzimela, saying he was
obsessed with affirmative action and consequently gave rise to
corruption and mismanagement in his ministry.
</P>
<P>
Ben Skosana, IFP caucus chairman and its chief foreign affairs
spokesman, has been appointed as the new Correctional Services
Minister. The appointment will take effect as soon as the
formalities have been finalized.
</P>
<P>
Skosana was IFP representative in the United Kingdom from 1987
to 1994, when he became a member of parliament. He has been a
member of the IFP central committee since 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
