<HEADLINE> Palestinian Negotiator Urges U.S. to Publicize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Top Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat Friday urged the United States to publicize its peace
initiative on a long overdue Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egyptian Voice of Arabs radio, Erekat once
again accused Israel of failing to put forward new ideas in the
recent talks on the Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"It is high time that the U.S. administration goes public with
its initiative," he told the radio.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
and Israel resumed first high-level talks in months on July 19 to
discuss the withdrawal, but the talks quickly hit a snag due to
Israel's refusal to accept the U.S. plan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly called on Israel to withdraw from
another 13.1 percent of the West Bank in exchange for PNA's
tougher crackdown on Islamic militants. The PNA has accepted the
proposal, but Israel is balking at it citing security concerns.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. first proposed its peace plan, the Palestinians
have been urging Washington to make public the plan so to put
pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
Erekat, who is also the PNA minister of local government, said
the Palestinians and Israel would continue talks next week on the
long-delayed Israeli troop pullback.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian leadership will meet after the return of (PNA)
President (Yasser) Arafat from abroad in order to determine
whether it is viable or not to continue these talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is visiting Turkey to seek support for the Palestinian
stand on the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
