<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Game Park to Control Elephant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's largest
nature reserve, the Kruger National Park, will adopt new measures
to deal with problems caused by growing elephant population, a
park official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The park would be divided into six regions, each having its
own priorities, so that the elephant population growth in
different areas would be monitored and controlled, the park's
conservation development manager Leo Braack said.
</P>
<P>
The extreme north and the southwestern regions of the
century-old park would become botanical reserves where particular
attention would be given to the conservation of the unique
vegetation.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 80 percent of the park will be divided into four
zones, two high elephant impact zones and two low elephant impact
zones.
</P>
<P>
In the high impact zones, elephants would be left to multiply
and consume vegetation without interference.
</P>
<P>
In the low impact zones, the elephant population would be
reduced annually by seven percent by relocating and culling
so-called problem animals.
</P>
<P>
Braack said the park reserves the right to using lethal
methods as the park has to ensure its wide bio-diversity is
conserved.
</P>
<P>
The Kruger park covers more than 19,000 square kilometers
along the country's northwestern border with Mozambique. It is
South Africa's biggest eco-tourism attraction with more than
800,000 visitors coming each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
