<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Treaty on Combating Crime Against Women to Be Signed at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South Asian leaders, ending their
summit here on Friday, said they would sign a convention on
combating the crime against women and children in the region at
their next gathering in Kathmandu, Nepal in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the seven-member South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) said in a declaration that they
welcome the finalization of the draft text on the Regional
Convention on Combating the Crime of Trafficking in Women and
Children for Prostitution.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the convention is to be signed at the 11th
SAARC summit next year.
</P>
<P>
At their Male summit last year, the South Asian leaders
expressed serious concern at the trafficking of women and children
within and between member countries, and pledged to coordinate
efforts of the member states to take effective measures to address
the problem.
</P>
<P>
The leaders at their Colombo summit also decided that the
convention be broadened to cover other purposes of trafficking in
women and children other than prostitution, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
They also called for exploring the feasibility of establishing
a regional fund for rehabilitation of the victims of trafficking
in women and children on a voluntary basis.
</P>
<P>
The leaders in their Colombo Declaration noted that many groups
of women and girl children in South Asia remain in disadvantaged
positions and lack equal opportunities for economic and social
development.
</P>
<P>
The leaders decided to establish a South Asian Cultural Unity
to promote the distinctive arts of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was based on the rich, complex and varied
plurality of cultural and religious traditions.
</P>
<P>
The leaders pointed out that the SAARC process could draw more
deeply from the vitality and strength of South Asia's shared
cultural heritage as a source influencing and enhancing creative
energies in all fields.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said that their countries continue to face the
serious threat of terrorism in all its forms and manifestation and
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reiterated their firm commitment to combat these
activities in the region.
</P>
<P>
The leaders recalled the adoption of the 1996 U.N. Declaration
on Measures to Eliminate International Terrorism and urged all
member states to work towards its implementation.
</P>
<P>
They also called for international action to prevent the abuse
of refugee conventions and to halt activities which help
terrorist groups to collect funds for their activities in South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
The leaders pointed out that two SAARC conferences on
cooperation in police matters had been held since 1996. The first
conference was held in Sri Lanka in July, 1996. The second was
held last year in the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
They called for the continued sharing of expertise with regard
to the different areas of police investigation, and investigation
of organized crimes and drug related crimes.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reiterated their commitment to the eradication of
poverty in the region as early as possible, preferably by the year
2002.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized the need to encourage maximum participation by
target
groups in the formulation and implementation of poverty
eradication
programs.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also pointed out that Human Resource Development
was a key
element in any poverty eradication program.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly they agreed that once the SAARC Center for Human
Resources Development was established in Islamabad it could look
into the
possibility of its contributing to the strengthening of the human
resources development components of the regional poverty
eradication
programs.
</P>
<P>
The leaders decided that discriminatory practices and
non-tariff barriers should be simultaneously removed on items in
respect of which tariff concessions are granted or have been
granted earlier.
</P>
<P>
Measures to remove structural impediments should also be taken
in order to move speedily towards the goal of the South Asian Free
Trade Area (SAFTA) which was agreed at the last summit in Male to
be established by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
SAARC launched the South Asian Preferential Trading Arrangement
(SAPTA) in December 1995 marking its first step towards the
creating of SAFTA.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reiterated the importance of achieving SAFTA and
towards achieving this, they decided to draft a comprehensive
treaty regime for creating a free trade area which will
incorporate binding time frames for freeing trade, measures to
facilitate trade and provisions to ensure equitable distribution
of benefits of trade to all states.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized the importance of finalizing the text or
regulatory framework by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the benefits of economic liberalization would
be more extensive through the promotion of trade creating joint
ventures, investment and trade in services such as tourism.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the seven member SAARC met in Colombo on July 29
to 31.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
