<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets UN Special Commission Head (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, in a
meeting with Richard Butler, executive chairman of the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) today, said that China, as a
permanent member of the United Nations Security Council, has
closely followed the Iraqi weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China is ready to play its role with other
Security Council members for a comprehensive implementation of the
UN Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
China and the international community have made a great effort
to find a peaceful solution in the weapons inspection crisis in
Iraq, Qian said, and that China has always held that Iraq should
follow the UN Security Council resolutions completely and fulfill
its obligation to destroy the weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The international community should assess Iraq's efforts at
implementing the resolutions fairly and in an objective way, he
said, and reach a factual conclusion on progress in the weapons
inspection.
</P>
<P>
China is in favor of a gradual easing of economic sanctions on
Iraq and finally lifting them, depending on how Iraq implements
the resolutions, Qian said, pointing out that the UN Special
Commission has made progress in its weapons inspection in its 7
years of existence.
</P>
</TEXT>
