<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Japanese PM Vows to Revive Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- New Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi vowed Friday to bring together "every possible force" to
rebuild Japan's troubled banking system and revitalize the ailing
economy.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, speaking at his first press conference since the
formation of his cabinet Thursday, said he has formed the "best
cabinet" for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Top priority for the new cabinet is to lead Japan out of the
prolonged economic stagnation, Obuchi said. He added that he was
confident the cabinet was capable of accomplishing the task.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister hopes more business persons and journalists
will help assist the cabinet in its efforts to overcome the
current economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi planned next week to launch a new economic advisory
panel that could draw up proposals quickly in order to help the
cabinet get through the current recession.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also pledged a cut of six trillion yen (about 41.8
billion U.S. dollars) in permanent income and corporate taxes, and
to implement a 10 trillion yen (about 69.6 billion dollars)
additional supplementary budget for fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
The issuing of bonds is under consideration to finance the new
measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Given the emergency need for the measures, the 1997 Fiscal
Structural Reform Law may have to be frozen, he said.
</P>
<P>
"By making every possible measure comprehensive, I hope the
economy will pick up and the (recovery) pace will double within a
year or two," Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also said his government and the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) will seek cooperation from opposition
parties on an issue-by-issue basis to pass economy-related
legislation through the opposition-dominated House of Councillors,
the upper house.
</P>
<P>
The new Japanese leader rejected the opposition's demand to
dissolve the House of Representatives, the lower house, and to
hold a general election after the LDP's major setback in the July
12 upper house election.
</P>
<P>
If the lower house is dissolved for the election, it will
create a political vacuum for two or three months, Obuchi said,
adding that no time should be wasted in preventing a further
deterioration of the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
