<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Women Demand Peaceful Resolution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of
Ethiopian women went on streets Friday and held a mass rally at
Masqual Square at central Addis Ababa, strongly demanding a
peaceful resolution to the Ethio-Eritrean crisis.
</P>
<P>
They want to urge the consolidation of efforts being deployed
to end the conflict peacefully, said Taddelech Hailemichael, Head
of Women's Affairs in the Ethiopian Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the rally, Hailemichael said the Ethiopian women
stand for peace and condemn attacks on innocent and defenseless
civilians.
</P>
<P>
The peaceful citizens, children and women should never be
targets in the war, she noted.
</P>
<P>
Hailemichael said the recent conflict "has not only disrupted
peace and development efforts," but "also placed an undue burden
on the civilian population and in particular women and children."
</P>
<P>
"During the first bombing raid, four pregnant women in labor
have lost their lives, 200,000 people have been displaced of
which three quarters are women and children," the official said.
</P>
<P>
"At the bombing in Mekele," she continued, "24 children under
the age of 18 died and 64 others were injured."
</P>
<P>
Friday's nationwide demonstration of women in Ethiopia was
organized by the newly-established National Steering Committee
for Women and Peace with aims to continue to seek peaceful
resolution to the crisis and solidarity with Eritrean women in
their support for peaceful resolution to the Ethio-Eritrean
border conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea, former Horn of Africa allies, fought a
bloody ground and air war between May and June 11 over the
disputed border territory of Badme and Sheraro.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea has resisted a clause in a peace plan sponsored by the
U.S. and Rwanda, endorsed by the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) to withdraw to territory it held before the conflict began
on May 6, and calls for international arbitration to settle the
border dispute with Addis.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the steering committee said that the
women in both Ethiopia and Eritrea should view the conflict as a
direct threat to their ability to live, work and ensure the
survival of their children.
</P>
<P>
"They have lost children, spouses, brothers and sons. If the
current conflict continues, their suffering will have been in
vain," the release added.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the committee called upon the women in Ethiopia and
throughout the world to participate in the demonstration for a
peaceful resolution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"At this historic juncture, women should focus their energies
on the future," the committee stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the OAU and African leaders will hold a
consultative meeting on the Ethio-Eritrean border crisis on
August 1-2 in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
