<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Urged to Attend Genetics Conference in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A group of Canadian geneticists are
urging their colleagues to attend a major genetics conference in
China next month, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 18th International Genetics Congress will begin in Beijing
on August 10. Some countries' scientists are boycotting the
congress because of their disapproval of China's three-year-old
genetics law.
</P>
<P>
Canadian geneticists, however, insist that communication goes
further than a boycott in fostering change, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"The law seems to have things about it we dislike, but we
weren't so smart ourselves not so long ago, and the situation
there is quite different, so we shouldn't be so judgmental," said
Dr. Clarke Fraser, chairman of ethics and public policy for the
Canadian College of Medical Geneticists and Biology at McGill
University in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the forced sterilization of some people
declared mentally insane during this century, which occurred in
some Western countries, including Canada.
</P>
<P>
"We have a moral obligation to share our historical experiences
with social policies," said Dr. Patrick MacLeod, chairman of the
Canadian College of Physicians and Surgeons Liaison Committee.
</P>
<P>
"We should be talking, not walking away from the issue," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Genetic associations in Britain, the Netherlands and Argentina
have sent official notice that they will boycott the gathering,
and they are encouraging other associations to do the same.
</P>
<P>
Scientists in other countries, including the United States,
have not taken an official stand, according to the Canadian
newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
