<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Foreign Exchange Reserves Decrease in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's foreign exchange reserves
totaled 272 million U.S. dollars at the end of September 1997,
decreasing by 96 million dollars as compared with that at the end
of March of the previous year, according to a latest official
review of the country's financial, economic and social conditions.
</P>
<P>
Of the total reserves of 272 million dollars, 77.78 million
were gold reserves and the rest 194.95 million were foreign
exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
The reserves also showed the lowest record in seven years since
March 1990 when it registered as 586 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of foreign exchange is seen as one of the main
economic difficulties encountered by the Myanmar government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Japanese government has extended to Myanmar a
total of 47.5 million dollars of grant-in-aid for debt relief
since June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in Myanmar totaled 7 billion dollars at the
end of March this year since the country enacted its Foreign
Investment Law in November 1988 when the country began to open its
door to the outside world and adopted a market-oriented economic
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
