<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stops Nationwide Finance, Tax Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China will stop its nationwide
inspections of financial affairs, taxation and commodities prices
beginning this year, according to the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
As the socialist market economy expands, a daily monitoring
network consisting of financial, taxation, auditing and other
social auditing organizations has been formed, standardizing daily
supervision.
</P>
<P>
This also makes it possible to stop nationwide inspections, a
ministry official explained.
</P>
<P>
Halting nationwide shock inspections does not suggest any
weakening or stopping of financial supervision, said the
official. "This meets the demand for improving the daily
supervisory network and increasing government's monitoring
functions to achieve the goal of tightening financial and economic
supervision with fewer repeated inspections," he said.
</P>
<P>
The inspection campaign, which has been practiced
annually across the country since 1985, was a special economic
supervisory tool used to ameliorate the financial chaos which
occurred in the early years of China's economic reform when the
old financial and taxation system was undergoing reform, and new
management mechanisms were yet to be established.
</P>
<P>
The past 13 years of nationwide inspections has saved
China 130 billion yuan in potential losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Exports More Leather Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China exported 3.7 billion
U.S. dollars worth of leather products in the first five months
this year, according to today's International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
This volume was a 6.4 percent growth over the same period last
year, when the nation's gross exports increased 8.2 percent during
the period.
</P>
<P>
The nation's exports of footballs, volleyballs and basketballs
saw a year-on-year growth of 17.3 percent in terms of export
volume, highest among all its leather products, but exports of
leather-shoe parts and similar products declined.
</P>
<P>
However, the average unit price of the sports balls was 0.18
dollars lower than a year ago, as was that of leather shoes, while
leather clothing and scarfs were sold well overseas.
</P>
<P>
Importing 35.9 percent more products from the mainland than
last year, Hong Kong accounted for 50.58 percent of China's
exports of leather products, topping Italy, which accounted for
13.13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the Republic of Korea, Thailand and Japan fell
dramatically by 46.4, 44.55, 119.1 percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
