<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Issues Employment-Agency Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Stranding Committee of the
Beijing Municipal People's Congress issued a regulation today to
tighten the management of local employment agencies.
</P>
<P>
Beginning September 1, employers who provide unreliable
information about employment vacancies for job hunters will be
fined 2,000 to 10,000 yuan, according to the regulation.
</P>
<P>
Selling job information to job seekers also will be regarded as
illegal, and such money will be confiscated, said Wang Zhenhua,
deputy-director of the Financial and Economic Committee of the
Standing Committee of the Beijing Municipal People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The regulation was approved today at the fourth meeting of the
Standing Committee of the Beijing Municipal People's Congress,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Some experts predict that during the 1998-2000 period there
will be 1.1 million people in Beijing needing help in finding jobs.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has now opened some 306 employment agencies which
provided job-finding services for a total of 850,000 people last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
