<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Asian Banks Face Insolvency as Economies Shrink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The banking systems in the
troubled economies of Asia face insolvency as the countries' real
economies shrink in the aftermath of last year's financial crisis,
an international rating agency warned here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a comprehensive review entitled the Outlook for Asian
Banking, Fitch IBCA said non-performing loans (NPLs) are growing
so rapidly that banks in the hardest hit economies are reporting
losses on such a scale that they will become insolvent.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the countries' governments, the international
relief agencies and the world's capital markets will have to
provide in excess of 100 billion U.S. dollars to recapitalize
their banking systems, said the agency which is formed from the
merger in 1997 of Fitch Investors Service, L.P. of the United
States and Europe's IBCA Group.
</P>
<P>
David Marshall, managing director of financial institution,
Asia for Fitch IBCA, said, "We are now in the middle of the
economic recessions that have followed last year's financial
crisis in Asia. This is causing the banking systems of the most
vulnerable economies to collapse under the weight of
non-performing loans."
</P>
<P>
"Governments are being forced to step in to rescue them," he
told a press conference here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The economic cost of the banking crises could be very
high. Indonesia faces an economic cost equivalent to 35 percent of
its GDP to recapitalize its banking system. In Thailand and
South Korea the cost could be between 25 percent and 30 percent
of their respective GDP.
</P>
<P>
The analyst pointed out, however, Hong Kong and Singapore have
both benefited from a high degree of government supervision and
prudent management of their banking systems.
</P>
<P>
Fitch IBCA expected NPLs in Hong Kong to remain below 10
percent of total lending by banks, a level that at worst will
result in a reduction in earnings. Singapore's banks should
tolerate a similar level of NPLs without announcing losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
