<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars on Asian Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economists suggested here
today that China should draw further lessons from the Asian
financial crisis and take counter-measures.
</P>
<P>
Established scholars from the prestigious Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences and other institutes pointed out at a forum that
these lessons relate to such issues as raising loans, dealing with
international capital, the export-oriented economy, and privatization
and liberalization of the economy.
</P>
<P>
They suggested that the government further tighten control
over the banking system, increase macro-control of the economy,
and focus on the quality instead of mere the quantity of foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Their views are specified in a report titled "Asian Financial
Crisis: the Latest Analysis and Counter-measures", which has been
published by the Social Sciences Documentation Publishing House.
</P>
<P>
This book is one of the most systematic and profound on the
Asian financial crisis which began in July last year and is
affecting nine countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Social Sciences has a research group
presently studying this issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
