<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses American Inspector of Spying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Friday accused an American
working on the U.N. arms inspection team of spying against Iraq
during visits to suspected weapon sites.
</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency said Baghdad strongly protested
against the conduct of espionage under the cover of the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), which is in charge of overseeing
the elimination of weapons of mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted an Iraqi National Monitoring Directorate
official as saying the American, Jason Gilbert, was caught
red-handed taking picture of subjects unrelated to his inspection
mission.
</P>
<P>
The source said that on July 28, while a group of
U.N. inspectors were on a diving mission in the Tigris riverside,
Gilbert, who supervised the operation, stealthily took a picture
of a passing train carrying military equipment, from behind a
large U.N. vehicle, using his own camera.
</P>
<P>
The source said the Iraqi escorts were witnesses to the
incident. Gilbert was asked to expose the film, a request he
immediately complied with.
</P>
<P>
The official called for an end to such espionage and
intelligence acts, and acts that have nothing to do with the work
of inspection, INA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
