<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Small Town in Floods  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Immense summer flooding has turned
Hukou, a small town adjacent to the mighty Yangtze River and
Poyang Lake, into the Venice of the Orient.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Hukou in east China's Jiangxi Province
climbed to around 22.5 meters on Thursday, 1.7 meters above the
town's ground level, said Zhou Xinhua, head of the Hukou
Hydrological Station.
</P>
<P>
All the town's streets have become water courses on which over
100 rubber rafts and wooden dinghies shuttle about. The
three-km-long Dazhong Road, the main avenue, is now the main
stream.
</P>
<P>
Floodwater flowed into the first floor of buildings along
Dazhong Road up to waist level, forcing residents to higher
floors. Out of curiosity, some children leaned out of windows on
the second and third floors to see what was happening outside.
</P>
<P>
State-owned grain stores have moved to a commanding height at
the western part of Dazhong Road, providing locals with rice and
noodles.
</P>
<P>
"We sold two or three kilos of rice at a price under the
government ceiling yesterday," said Zhang Yan, a saleswoman at
Ximen Grain Store.
</P>
<P>
Flooding has submerged two of the three vegetable markets in
Hukou, leaving only one partially operating. A dozen individual
peddlers sell seasonal vegetables such as water spinach, Chinese
wax gourd, tomatoes and potatos, and vegetable prices remain
roughly the same as before.
</P>
<P>
Dried-vegetable vendor Tang Renzhuang said, "I can earn more
than 100 yuan a day since floods hit the area, doubling the daily
income of ordinary days."
</P>
<P>
Local residents have replaced bicycles, the most popular means
of transport in China, with boats when they go to buy vegetables
and grain. Many boats are propelled by two people, with one
polling the boat and the other pulling oars. In narrow streets,
they have to strike the boat forward by pulling along the walls of
buildings on both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Small Town in Floods   (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The phones are working in homes and electricity and drinking
water are also available," said Chen Jinchai, a secondary school
teacher who stayed behind to take care of the residential
building. All the people in her 15 neighbor households have been
evacuated to safer places.
</P>
<P>
Liao Kaibo, secretary of the Hukou County Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), and county magistrate Wang Ruzhuo
inspected the flood-affected areas by boat.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the Hukou County Government sign standing at the
entrance to the government building is submerged in water, but all
government functionaries are standing fast at their posts.
</P>
<P>
The local post office built a barrier in front of its entrance
to keep the water away, and drained off the water inside with a
pump. All kinds of telecommunications services are working
normally.
</P>
<P>
A local resident said, "Daily life here is passable but far
from comfortable. We have no fear but feel agitated." This
reflects the minds of the 30,000 residents of Hukou.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 90 percent of the town seat has been
inundated, and more than 98,400 people have already been evacuated
with no reports of casualties, said Pei Muchun, deputy head of the
county flood control headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The flooding has brought about direct economic losses of 380
million yuan to Hukou so far this month, seven times the county's
entire revenue in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Civil Affairs show that floods
have killed more than 1,000 people across China this year. They
have also destroyed 2.9 million houses and decimated 9 million
hectares of crops, causing direct economic losses estimated at
over 84 billion yuan (10 billion U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
