<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Air Quality Continues to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China's major cities continued to
enjoy better air quality over the past week, according to the
latest report released by the China Environmental Monitoring
Center.
</P>
<P>
The number of cities enjoying excellent atmosphere quality hit
a record 15 between July 24-30, according to the report. With the
exception of Yantai in Shangdong Province, the 15 cities,
including Shenzhen, Zhuhai and Xiamen, are all located either in
the Yangtze River Valleys or south of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Beijing reported good air quality during the period, along with
Shanghai, Nanjing and Guangzhou cities.
</P>
<P>
The number of cities with slight air pollution dropped from
nine to seven when compared to the previous week. The seven cities
-- Xi'an, Hohhot, Lanzhou, Taiyuan, Jinan, Zhengzhou and Xining,
all reported high levels of suspended particles.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of China's cities witnessed either overcast or cloudy
days over the past week, with related conditions playing a major
role in purifying the atmosphere.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
