<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Technology Creates 2.87 Million Jobs for Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- While "laid-off" has become one of
the most popular words among urban Chinese and the media,
fast-growth high-tech ventures in China have created over 2.86
million jobs for the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, vice-minister of Science and Technology, said at a
news conference here today that his ministry is discussing with
banks and the Ministry of Finance the proposal for establishing a
risk investment system for high-tech ventures in a bid to
encourage their development.
</P>
<P>
China's 53 high-and new-technology development zones have
created 1.47 million jobs, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Torch Program Office of the Ministry of
Science and Technology said another 1.47 million people are
working in high-tech ventures in state-level high-tech zones that
were designated by the science and technology commissions at the
provincial level.
</P>
<P>
Beijing now has more high-tech ventures than any other city in
China. Statistics indicate that Beijing has registered more than
3,000 high-tech ventures employing 120,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The official said electronics and information ventures rank
first among China's high-tech enterprises, followed by biological
technology, new materials, energy saving and environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that over 28 percent of the employees in
high-tech ventures have a college education.
</P>
<P>
The Torch Program is aimed at the commercialization and
industrialization of scientific discoveries.
</P>
<P>
So far, 13,400 high-tech ventures have been registered in the
country's 53 high-tech development zones. Their 1997 income from
industrial production and trade reached 338 billion yuan (nearly
40 billion U.S. dollars.) in 1997, 47 percent more than 1996.
</P>
<P>
A high-tech fair in Beijing is being arranged by the Ministry
of Science and Technology from August 6-10 to display China's
10-year achievements in high-tech development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Ties Vital:  U.S.-Aussie Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Australia and the United States
said here Friday they acknowledged the profound importance of the
Sino-U.S. relationship to the Asia Pacific regional security and
prosperity with both sides agreeing a "one-China" policy best
served the region's interest in stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique released here Friday, U.S. and
Australian foreign and defense ministers said Australia and the
U.S. "emphasized the essentiality of comprehensive and practical
engagement with China, and of supporting China's development as a
stable, open and prosperous power, and a strong and constructive
partner in the international community."
</P>
<P>
The document, which focused on the Asian financial crisis and
recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan and their implications
for regional and global stability and security, was released
following two-day annual Australia-United States Ministerial
Consultations (AUSMIN).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation was led by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Defense Secretary William Cohen, and Australia were
represented by Foreign Minister Alexander Downer and Defense
Minister Ian McLachlan.
</P>
<P>
"Both (U.S. and Australian) governments agreed that a
'one-China' policy best served the (Asia Pacific) region's
interest in stability and prosperity," said the communique, which
does not go into detail.
</P>
<P>
"One China" policy refers to the policy of recognizing the
government of the People's Republic of China as the sole and
legitimate government of China and Taiwan as part of China.
</P>
<P>
"Australia welcomed the successful visit of (U.S.) President
Clinton to China in June-July 1998, and congratulated the United
States and China on recent progress made in their relationship,"
said the document.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and Australia welcomed recent positive
developments in relations between Japan and China, and between
Japan and Russia, as important steps in fostering the Asia
Pacific's growing sense of community and cooperative endeavor."
</P>
<P>
AUSMIN has been held regularly since 1985, but the AUSMIN held
here in 1996 saw the political and military relations between the
United States and Australia improving substantially following
Australian Prime Minister John Howard took power in March, 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
