<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Grant Two More Cell Phone Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will grant two
more cellular communications licenses, possibly in early 1999,
the country's telecommunications authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications Minister Jay Naidoo welcomed a
recommendation by the South African Telecommunications Regulatory
Authority (SATRA) that two new cellular phone licenses be issued,
saying the move would bring about more competition and benefit
the consumers.
</P>
<P>
SATRA said in a notice published in the government gazette
dated July 31 that South Africa could sustain another two
networks.
</P>
<P>
There are currently two mobile phone operators in the country,
Vodacom and MTN. They strongly oppose the awarding of more
cellular phone licenses, saying the market is saturated.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo, who was handed the SATRA report earlier this month,
said in a statement Friday that the ministry accepted the
recommendations, which is "comprehensive and balanced."
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see the two new operators in the market as
soon as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will soon issue invitation for tenders, and then
it is SATRA's responsibility to select the best operators, Naidoo
said.
</P>
<P>
"I want to emphasize that SATRA will be responsible for
evaluating the tenders and for awarding the licenses," the
minister said, adding that it would take a few months to evaluate
the bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
