<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Records Trade Surplus in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa notched up a
higher-than-expected trade surplus of 1.07 billion Rand (175
million U.S. Dollars) in June.
</P>
<P>
This was half of May's exceptionally high surplus of about 2
billion Rand (328 million Dollars), but much better than
expectations of about 500 million Rand surplus.
</P>
<P>
Imports rose from 10.3 billion Rand (1.69 billion Dollars) in
May to 11.3 billion Rand (1.85 billion Dollars) in June while
exports remained static at 12.3 billion Rand (2 billion Dollars),
the South African Revenue Service said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Economists had not expected another surge in exports after
May's spectacular rise, and were pleased that the trade balance
had continued in a respectable surplus after deficits in March
and April, according to reports of South African newspapers
Friday.
</P>
<P>
On a cumulative basis, the trade surplus for the first six
months of the year was about 3 billion Rand (492 million
Dollars), down from about 4 billion Rand (656 million Dollars)
for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Machinery imports were once again the main driving force
behind import growth. Machinery imports excluded, import growth
was soft, at only 4.6 percent year on year in the first half of
the year.
</P>
<P>
But economists said the strong growth in machinery imports is
not cause for concern, as they would add to gross domestic fixed
investment, which is necessary to improve the productive capacity
of the economy and enhance growth potential.
</P>
<P>
Export growth was being hampered by the poor performance of
gold and diamond exports. The category containing these exports
had fallen 8.4 percent year on year.
</P>
<P>
Barring chemical products, exports in other categories were
showing very respectable growth, with machinery and transport
exports recording the highest growth of about 20 percent year on
year.
</P>
<P>
Excluding gems and precious metals, export growth had been
14.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the outlook for the trade surplus in the second
half of this year was fairly positive due to the sharp
depreciation in the Rand in the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Rand, which has lost over 25 percent its value against the
Dollar this year, would help to raise revenues from commodity
exports even if volumes remained flat, the analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed higher Friday as persistent
institutional buying on index-linked bluechips throughout the day
dampened the spirit of sellers.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stock Composite Index gained
13.12 points to 402.65, the all-share Emas Index added 2.61 points
to 102.97, the Industrial notched up 26.06 points to 836.68 and
the Second Board was 0.27 of a point higher at 89.06.
</P>
<P>
Gainers overwhelmed losers by 358 to 198 while 185 counters
were unchanged, 181 counters untraded and 38 counters suspended.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover stood at 115.905 million shares valued at
183.047 million ringgit (about 44.214 million U.S. dollars) from
112.844 million shares worth 187.786 million ringgit (about 45.358
million U.S. dollars) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Main board volume rose to 112.428 million shares valued at
179.146 million ringgit (about 43.271 million U.S. dollars) from
Thursday's 109.133 million shares worth 184.150 million ringgit
(about 44.48 million U.S dollars).
</P>
<P>
On the second board, turnover declined to 3.477 million shares
worth 3.901 million ringgit (about 0.942 million U.S. dollars)
from 3.711 million shares amounting to 3.636 million ringgit
(about 0.878 million U.S. dollars) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Off market deals decreased to 7.214 million shares from 12.290
million shares but increased in value to 34.131 million ringgit
(about 8.244 million U.S. dollars) from 13.150 million ringgit
(about 3.17 million U.S. dollars) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 7.848
million shares traded on the main board, industrial products 8.136
million shares, construction 12.364 million shares,
trading/services 35.777 million shares, infrastructure 1.363
million shares, finance 21.577 million shares, hotels 408,000
shares, properties 12.168 million shares, plantation 3.896 million
shares, mining 335,600 shares, and trusts 130,000 shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
