<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Imports Could Stave off Price Hikes in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The recent deals sealed by
South Africa's state power utility, Eskom, to import power from
Mozambique and Zambia could stave off local power price hikes in
the medium term, Business Day paper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Eskom signed agreements this month with Cahora Bassa in
Mozambique and the Zambian Electricity Supply Corporation (Zesco)
to buy their electricity.
</P>
<P>
Both deals reduced the pressure on Eskom to build new power
stations, which would require a lot capital investment, Eskom
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The company said Thursday that the move would not adversely
affect the local price of electricity.
</P>
<P>
Eskom officials said earlier that power prices might be
increased to help fund its commitment to provide power to more
people in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming commercialization of the utility, which means
it would have to pay taxes and dividends in the future, could
also push up the prices.
</P>
<P>
Eskom reportedly bought 900 MW of uninterrupted power from
Cahora Bassa at 3 cents (0.5 U.S. cents) a kilowatt hour for this
year and 4 cents (0.66 U.S. cents) for 1999. After that the deal
would be revised.
</P>
<P>
The deal with Zesco is understood to be similar, but involving
only 120 MW, the paper said. These power figures were
comparatively small in terms of Eskom's total capacity of nearly
40,000 MW.
</P>
<P>
Concern was expressed that Eskom was to import power at a
higher price than it cost to produce locally.
</P>
<P>
Eskom's raw material cost is estimated at 2.5 cents, although
it sells electricity at 20 to 30 cents to retail consumers after
provision for overheads and growth.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has one of the cheapest power prices in the
world, at 17.5 cents (2.9 U.S. cents) per kilowatt hour,
according to a survey released earlier this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
