<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Back from Visit to France, Morocco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
return home Friday morning from a high-profile visit to France and
Morocco in an attempt to rescue the faltering peace process.
</P>
<P>
He was in Paris to substantiate a Franco-Egyptian initiative on
an international conference on the Mideast peace process in case
current effort to restart the peace wheel fails.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also attended the 17th session of the Al Quds
(Jerusalem) Committee of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference which wound up in Casablanca, Morocco on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The top Egyptian diplomat told reporters upon arrival that he
will submit a detailed report to President Hosni Mubarak on the
outcome of the Committee's meetings, and the results of talks he
has held with Iraqi, Syrian, Moroccan, Iranian and Palestinian
counterparts on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen foreign ministers of the Islamic and Arab world issued
a final communique, urging rethinking relations with Israel, and
considering closing their missions and bureaux until the Jewish
state fulfills peace commitments.
</P>
<P>
The committee also decided to set up a special fund to support
Palestinians in East Jerusalem to counter the expansion of Israeli
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that his report also involves details of
his visit to Paris, his meeting with French President Jacques
Chirac and with his French counterpart Hubert Vedrine on the
developments of the peace process and the Egyptian-French
initiative to salvage the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's trip to Paris has reportedly turned the initiative
into a plan and thrashed out details of a viable option to the
ongoing U.S. mediation bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
