<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Rise Marginally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Early gains inspired by rises on
United States and Japanese markets were tempered by late selling
of shares of News Corp. and BHP to leave Australian shares only
marginally higher Friday.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index rose 3.3 points to 2,704.6 off an
early high of 2,735.2 points, with volumes unusually strong.
</P>
<P>
General sentiment was also seen improving as the Japanese
reform process began and overnight U.S. wages numbers provided
further indications of a strong growth, low inflation economy.
</P>
<P>
"There was a very positive reaction to the economic numbers
that came out of the U.S. market Thursday night that allayed fears
we may see an interest rate rise any time soon," Hartley Poynton
broker Ned Shamay said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 12.7 points to 4,777.8 with most
leading stocks solid and some good gain among the mid-range
companies.
</P>
<P>
Insurance giant AMP, which roared ahead this week prior to
Monday's inclusion in market indices, posted a more mild rise
Friday, closing 15.1 cents higher, on a volume of 13 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
Of the major banks, ANZ was the improver after missing out
Thursday, adding 17 cents, Commonwealth Bank rose 12.2 cents,
National Australia Bank edged five cents lower and Westpac dropped
ten cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished 5.3 points lower at 1,027.2
despite a strong gold sector.
</P>
<P>
Diversified giant BHP dropped 26.4 cents amid reports of
offshore institutional selling.
</P>
<P>
Of the other diversifieds North gained three cents, Rio Tinto
was 13 cents lower and WMC finished steady at 4.94 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished three points higher at 1,052.9 as the
bullion price edged up from 289.60 U.S. dollars per ounce to
finish at 289.65.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 383.96 million shares traded at a value of 1.874
billion Australian dollars (1.148 billion U.S. dollars), with
rises topping falls 599 to 441. 
</P>
</TEXT>
