<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Slips Lower in Light Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar slipped
lower Friday in light trade ahead of a Monday banking holiday in
some states.
</P>
<P>
Trapped in a tight range of 61.00 to 61.20 U.S. cents, the
currency settled into the close at 61.14, down from 61.36
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia treasury manager Paul Macarounas said
despite the quiet dealings in terms of range for the currency,
there was good interest from both sides of the market.
</P>
<P>
The unit received a scare when the Japanese yen fell against
the U.S. dollar overnight after new Japanese Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa said market forces should determine the level of
the yen, downplaying the prospect of further central bank
intervention to support the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
Miyazawa said intervention was only appropriate in "extreme"
cases. He Friday tempered those comments by saying they were just
a statement of "a general principle."
</P>
<P>
Japan is Australia's major export destination and the
Australian dollar has been monitoring events to resuscitate the
Asian country's struggling economy.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the session here the Australian dollar was buying
87.76 yen from 87.32 on Thursday, and 1.0872 German marks from
1.0862. 
</P>
</TEXT>
