<HEADLINE> Nigeria Releases New Guidelines for Oil Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
approved new guidelines for exporting crude oil in an apparent
move to check abuse in the export of the country's major foreign
currency earner.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines, approved by Head of State, General
Abdulsalam Abubakar, was issued Thursday in Abuja, the federal
capital. It will take into immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines recognize four categories of companies as
qualified to export crude oil from Nigeria:
</P>
<P>
Upstream investors who have acquired an Oil Prospecting
Licenses and must have completed a minimum amount of the work on
the concession;
</P>
<P>
Companies that have built an export oil refinery in Nigeria;
</P>
<P>
Bonafide end-users who own a refinery and retail outlets
abroad;
</P>
<P>
Established and globally recognized large volume traders.
</P>
<P>
All the applicants must have a minimum annual turnover of 100
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
They must also have committed to the development of the
Nigerian economy by inverting in any number of investment
opportunities in the oil industry or other sectors, or as an
alternative, have meaningful investment in oil producing areas.
</P>
<P>
Successful applicants as end-users and large volume traders
are required to post a one million Dollar performance bond
through a reputable Nigerian bank in addition to satisfying the
regular crude oil contract provision.
</P>
<P>
The bond will be forfeited to the Nigerian government, if
after six months of the signing of the crude oil contract, the
investment has not been made or there is no evidence of a
commitment to do so. Besides, the oil contract will automatically
terminate.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines stipulate that crude oil export shall now
be on the basis of confirmed irrevocable letters of credit only.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
