<HEADLINE> Kluivert Transfer to Man United Agreed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Patrick Kluivert and his team of
financial advisers will fly to England within the next two days to
discuss personal terms after Manchester United and AC Milan agreed
a fee of nine million pounds (14.8 million U.S. dollars) for the
Dutch World Cup striker.
</P>
<P>
The deal would take United manager Alex Ferguson's summer
spending spree to 24 million pounds, but there remains a question
of Kluivert's wage demands, which is believed to be in the region
of 50,000 pounds a week.
</P>
<P>
But to clinch the player's signature, United manager Alex
Ferguson will almost certainly have to break the rigid wage
structure at Old Trafford.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson has operated a 20,000 pounds a week ceiling to avoid
dressing room jealousy but this may have to go to persuade
Kluivert to play in the English premier league.
</P>
<P>
The imminent arrival of Kluivert will not end Ferguson's
interest in Dwight Yorke, the Aston Villa forward.
</P>
<P>
Martin Edwards, the United chairman, revealed that the club
hoped to bring in the two players before the start of the Premier
league on August 15.
</P>
<P>
"It doesn't mean our interest in Yorke has dropped...it just
means we can be a bit more relaxed about the situation now.
</P>
<P>
"Our bid for Kluivert has been accepted but we have not had an
opportunity to speak to the player because he went on holiday
after the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously he will want to speak to Alex Ferguson and the two
of them will get together as soon as possbile," he said.
</P>
<P>
If United complete the Kluivert deal, Ferguson will have
sufficient striking power to use Teddy Sheringham, Andy Cole or
Ole Gunnar Solskjaer as bait in a player-plus-cash offer for Yorke.
</P>
<P>
Villa manager John Gregory has put a 16 million pounds price
tag on the Trinidad and Tobago international.
</P>
<P>
United have offered David May, Denis Irwin, Teddy Sheringham
and Ole Gunnar Solskjaer, plus cash, at different times to try to
tempt Gregory to sell and now they are reported to be ready to
offer Andy Cole plus five million pounds.
</P>
<P>
Gregory said: "I always thought that if United were to sign a
top class striker then the chase for Dwight Yorke would end.
</P>
<P>
"But my view now is that Alex Ferguson probably sees Kluivert
and Yorke playing together.
</P>
<P>
"Kluivert is what you would consider to be a number nine and so
is Andy Cole. They seem too similar to me to be playing alongside
each other," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
