<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Progress at Indo-Pakistan Talks on Resumption of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Senior Pakistani and Indian
officials have failed to make any progress at their talks in
Colombo. Sri Lanka, on the possible resumption of the dialogue
between the two countries, a Pakistani spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The Pakistan-India dialogue remains stalemated and no progress
has been made in Colombo," spokesman Tariq Altaf told a press
conference, adding that Pakistan hoped to keep in tough with India
"through diplomatic channels" on the issue.
</P>
<P>
At their talks Wednesday on the sidelines of a summit of South
Asian leaders in the Sri Lankan capital, Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif and his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee, who
would meet again next month during a Non-Aligned Movement summit
in South Africa's Durban, agreed that the dialogue, which broke
off last September in New Delhi, should be resumed.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' foreign secretaries were asked to meet
Wednesday and Thursday here to work out the "modalities" for the
resumption of the dialogue, Vajpayee told a press conference
shortly after his meeting with Sharif.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign secretaries of Pakistan and India have met twice
on July 29 and 30 to overcome the procedural as well as
substantive impediments to the resumption of Pakistan-India talks.
It has not been possible for them to reach an agreement," Altaf
said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have failed to reach any agreement on the
resumption of the dialogue due to their deep differences over the
issues of peace and security and Jammu and Kashmir, according to
the Pakistani spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India have fought three wars since their
independence from Britain in 1947, two of them over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India resumed their dialogue at the foreign
secretary level in March last year after a three-year hiatus. But
the dialogue broke off again last September.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan now wants the dialogue to be resumed on the basis of
an eight-point agreement reached between the two sides in
Islamabad on June 23 last year. The first two points, or agenda
items, deal with the issues of peace and security and Jammu and
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The first two items in "the sequential order of the agreed
agenda" must be dealt with "specifically and substantially" on a
priority basis, particularly in view of the worsening security
situation in the region in the aftermath of the nuclear tests
carried out in May this year by India as well as by Pakistan,
which did so in a tit-for-tat manner, according to Altaf.
</P>
<P>
India, on the other hand, insists that the dialogue should
start afresh. Altaf accused India of having "resiled on the
understandings" reached in Islamabad and said no basis therefore
exists for the resumption of the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
No Indian officials in Colombo were available for comment on
the talks.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani spokesman pointed to the nuance of the wording
the two prime ministers used in their respective statements issued
at their separate press conferences Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Indian prime minister unilaterally announced that the two
sides had agreed on the resumption of talks," whereas "the prime
minister of Pakistan said that the two sides had agreed to
continue the talks at the next available opportunity," Altaf
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"At the heart of the problem lies the rigid and inflexible
position which India continues to maintain in its refusal to
address the issues of peace and security and Jammu and Kashmir
dispute," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani spokesman also said his country remains ready for
talks on the resumption of the dialogue "whenever India is willing
to do so," and expressed the hope that the two sides would remain
in touch "through diplomatic channels to overcome the
difficulties" standing in the way of the resumption of the
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the local Island newspaper published
Friday, Sharif said the outcome of his talks with his Indian
counterpart was "zero."
</P>
<P>
The Indian prime minister was not willing to focus on Kashmir
prominently nor did he want Kashmir to figure prominently in a
joint communique, according to Sharif.
</P>
<P>
"If that was the position, what is the point in having these
talks because Kashmir was the root cause of all the conflicts
between India and Pakistan. We did not want to hold talks for the
sake of talks but for the talks to succeed," Sharif was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The prime ministers of Pakistan and India, as the spokesman
announced, would have their next meeting on the sidelines of a
summit of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) scheduled for August this
year in Durban, South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
