<HEADLINE> UN Calls on European Countries to Prevent Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
Commission for Europe (UN/ECE) has called on European countries to
prevent forest fires by improving management of forests.
</P>
<P>
"These fires do not break out only by chance or due to ill
will," Jorge Najera, forest fire expert in the Timber Section of
the UN/ECE, said here Thursday. "It is, above all, a social
phenomenon closely related to land use issues."
</P>
<P>
Fires due to natural causes, such as those caused by lightning,
only represent 2.1 percent of all fires in France and 4.3 percent
in Spain, according to the UN/ECE.
</P>
<P>
Most of the fires are still man made, due to negligence, said
the organization.
</P>
<P>
There is therefore an urgent need to intensify the education
campaigns and to sensitize the public, especially children, so
that they learn to respect and protect their inheritance.
</P>
<P>
"For this reason it is of vital importance to be able to better
manage forest fires, which every year provoke damage to this
unique natural resource and cause human losses, especially among
those fighting fires," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
