<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asian Leaders Call For Strengthening Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South Asian leaders ending their
tenth summit in Colombo Friday called for strengthening regional
economic cooperation, recognizing the rich potential for
productive equitable regional cooperation among the governments
and people of South Asia which accounts for a fifth of the world
population.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration ending their three-day summit the seven member
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) decided
that deeper preferential tariff concessions should be extended to
products which are being actively traded among the members.
</P>
<P>
The leaders decided that discriminatory practices and
non-tariff barriers should be simultaneously removed on items in
respect of which tariff concessions are granted or have been
granted earlier.
</P>
<P>
Measures to remove structural impediments should also be taken
in order to move speedily towards the goal of the South Asian Free
Trade Area (SAFTA) which was agreed at the last summit in Male to
be established by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
SAARC launched the South Asian Preferential Trading Arrangement
(SAFTA) in December 1995 marking its first step towards the
creating of SAFTA.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reiterated the importance of achieving SAFTA and
towards achieving this, they decided to draft a comprehensive
treaty regime for creating a free trade area which will
incorporate binding time frames for freeing trade, measures to
facilitate trade and provisions to ensure equitable distribution
of benefits of trade to all states.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized the importance of finalizing the text or
regulatory framework by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the benefits of economic liberalization would
be more extensive through the promotion of trade creating joint
ventures, investment and trade in services such as tourism.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Israeli Labor Tries to Settle Orr Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to defuse the
crisis caused by the derogatory remarks about Sephardic Jews by
its member Ori Orr, Israeli opposition Labor party has decided to
suspend Orr from all his official party positions.
</P>
<P>
During a special meeting Thursday night, Labor leader Ehud
Barak told the party's Knesset (parliament) members that Orr would
not be allowed to speak on behalf of the Labor faction in the
Knesset plenum.
</P>
<P>
And Orr would be permanently removed from the Knesset's Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee and from its subcommittee on the
security services, as well as from the Labor faction leadership
and a forum of senior party officials, Barak added.
</P>
<P>
Orr, an Ashkenazi Jew and ex-army general, said that he
accepted the party decision.
</P>
<P>
Orr set off a public outcry Wednesday in an interview he gave
to local daily Haaretz, in which he said that some Sephardic Jews
"are not curious about their surroundings," are not "Israeli in
their character" and cannot be talked to like other people.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Jewish population is roughly split among Sephardic
and Ashkenazi Jews. Sephardic Jews with middle eastern descent
had suffered discrimination after arriving in early 1950s at the
hands of the ruling Ashkenazi Jews of European descended elite.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman expressed anger and "terrible
sorrow" over Orr's statements, saying that Orr should do some
serious soul-searching and consider whether he is suitable for
political life.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu used Orr's remarks to blast
the entire Labor party and make political gain. He noted that
some Labor members continued to run counter to the principle of
"equality and unity."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Orr's statement are perceived in Labor to have
caused grave damage to the party, which has been making intensive
efforts to rehabilitate its relations with the Sephardic
communities.
</P>
<P>
Labor hopes to win some support from Sephardic communities,
which traditionally voted for Likud, in order to ascend to power
in the 2000 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's decision to suspend Orr did not satisfy all the
Labor members, who also demanded Orr's resignation from the
Knesset.
</P>
<P>
They said that as long as Orr is in the party's leadership, his
statements can be used against Labor in the election campaign and
cause serious damage.
</P>
<P>
Barak refused to say whether he had asked Orr to resign. But he
is due to convene a Labor central committee meeting on Sunday to
decide what further measures should be taken against Orr.
</P>
<P>
His associates indicated that it is very difficult for Barak to
resolve the crisis without Orr's quit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
