<HEADLINE> Water Level at Dongting Lake Hits New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The water level at Dongting Lake
in central China's Hunan Province rose to 35.33 meters at 06:00
a.m. (Beijing time) today, 0.02 meters higher than the former
record high. The water is continuing to rise slowly from heavy
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The latest report from the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters said the water level at Poyang Lake reached
its highest of the current flood season, standing at 22.58 meters
this morning, 0.78 meters higher than the previous all-time high,
at the Hukou Hydrological Station. By 06:00 a.m. the water level
had dropped to 22.52 meters.
</P>
<P>
The water level at the Hankou Hydrological Station in Hubei
Province registered 29.07 meters on Thursday afternoon, the second
highest since the station was built in 1865. And for some period
of time the water level fell to 29.02 meters, but rose again to
29.06 meters at 07:00 a.m. today and continued to rise, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecasts predict that rainfall along some parts of the
Yangtze River will ease up in the next few days. However, the
middle and lower reaches of the river are expected to continue to
see rain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
