<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Publish Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Top Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat Friday called on the United States to make known its
initiative on Israeli redeployment in order to save the faltering
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Since Israel had come up with nothing new to push forward the
peace process, it is high time that the U.S. administration went
public with its initiative," he told the Egyptian Voice of Arabs
radio station.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came as the Palestinian-Israeli direct talks failed
to produce an agreement on the U.S. proposal, which calls for a
further 13.1 percent Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank in
return for Palestinian security guarantee.
</P>
<P>
Erekat added the two sides would resume talks next week and
their contacts were under way. "Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu is trying to exploit these meetings to claim there is
something new in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace-making has been stalled since
March 1997 over Israel's construction of a new settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem and long-delayed withdrawal from the Palestinian
land.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian leadership will meet after the return of
President (Yasser) Arafat from abroad in order to determine
whether it is viable or not to continue these talks," Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
European and U.S. moves were afoot to put the Middle East peace
process back on track, he said, asking Washington to come up with
a full report on the fate of its initiative and say who has
accepted it and who has not.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has been resisting the U.S. proposal,
which has been accepted by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said the Egyptian-French call for an international
conference on the Middle East peace process should complement the
U.S. initiative in helping reach a final solution.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and French President Jacques
Chirac put forward the overture to rescue the peace process during
their talks in Paris in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
