<P>
-- Directly elected mayors with executive powers are to be
allowed in every English town and city under radical government
plans to restore public confidence and enthusiasm in town hall
politics.
</P>
<P>
Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The British government Thursday launched the most sweeping
overhaul of financial regulation for more than a decade by
publishing a draft bill to set up a single regulator with an
unprecedented range of powers and responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- British Prime Minister Tony Blair was accused Thursday night
of sidelining Parliament by delivering his first "state of the
nation" address to a hand-picked group of ministers and civil
servants in the garden of No 10 rather than to the Commons.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- Consumers could soon enjoy lower food prices after the Office
of Fair Trading Thursday launched an investigation into Britain's
largest supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- The first transplant of an animal organ into a human being is
within sight in Britain after a government announcement Thursday
which dismayed rights campaigners and others who fear that new
diseases might spread from animals through the human population.
