<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Agrees on Security Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) have agreed on the
draft mechanism which provides for its intervention in the
internal affairs of its member countries.
</P>
<P>
A communique provided by the ECOWAS secretariat Thursday in
Abuja, capital of Nigeria, stated that the body's intervention in
the internal affairs of member states will be a "fait accompli"
where "conflict in a country threatens to trigger a humanitarian
disaster and poses a serious threat to peace and security in the
sub-region".
</P>
<P>
There will also be such interventions when "threats to the
security in the sub-region erupt following the overthrow or
attempted overthrow of a democratically elected government", the
Guardian reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not say when and where the communique was
signed.
</P>
<P>
However, observers noted the consensus is coming at the time
when calls that the west African peacekeeping force ECOMOG be
sent to crisis-ravaged Guinea Bissau has reached a peak.
</P>
<P>
Ministers of defense and foreign affairs from ECOWAS member states
had earlier this month met in Cote d'Ivoire to work out the details
of ECOMOG's intervention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Business Confidence Rebounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Business confidence in New
Zealand improved for the second month in a row in July, with
exporters particularly bullish, the New Zealand Press Association
(NZPA) said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted NZ National Bank chief economist Brendan O'Donovan as
saying that optimists outnumbered pessimists 41 percent to 26
percent for a net balance of 15 percent expecting general business
conditions to improve over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
That beat last month's net 12 percent optimism shown by the
bank's survey of business opinion, O'Donovan told NZPA Friday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the standout feature was the buoyant outlook
among exporters.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange rate (for the NZ dollar) has fallen and firms
that export to anywhere except Asia are enjoying life," he said.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers were particularly optimistic with a net 54
percent expecting a lift in exports, the highest confidence level
for more than three years, O'Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
But the lower currency had a downside with a net 19 percent
expecting higher prices, the highest level for three years, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"When activity picks up there is a backlog of inflation
pressures to come through," the economist predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
