<HEADLINE> China Set to Build Pipeline for Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China will begin construction of a
1,540-km pipeline, the largest contracted foreign oil project in
the nation's history, in Sudan at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the Pipeline Department of the China
National Petroleum Corp (CNPC), noted that China won the project
bid in 1997 amidst fierce competition with more than 30
international oil companies.
</P>
<P>
Chinese engineers and technicians have completed surveying and
designing of the project. Some 2,000 engineers and construction
workers are currently working in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Site preparations are underway and work is proceeding smoothly,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline, which link a major oilfield in the south to Sudan
Port in the north, will have a designed annual pumping capacity of
15 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
