<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise For Fourth Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose for the fourth
consecutive trading day Friday as pledges by the new Japanese
government of large income tax cuts and a "soft landing" for the
country's bad loan crisis fueled market optimism.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange advanced 177.37 points, or 1.09
percent, from Thursday's close to finish at 16,378.97.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, rose 13.85 points or 1.11 percent to 1,262.04.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 379 million
shares from 365.09 million shares Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Fuji Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The first full day of trading following Thursday's launch of a new
cabinet under Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi got an early boost via
buybacks of big-name shares such as Nippon Steel, Hitachi and NEC.
</P>
<P>
The rise occurred amid a steep fall in the yen against the U.S.
dollar and a new backdrop of economic gloom. The government announced
Friday that Japan's jobless rate in June hit a record high of 4.3
percent since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Some traders said the gains were supported by newly appointed
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa's comments that an income tax cut
exceeding 6 trillion yen (about 41.8 billion dollars) will be
implemented in order to boost consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered losers 692 to 394, with 168 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar stayed firmly over
143 yen after fears of intervention to prop up the yen were quelled by
Miyazawa.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 143.77-80 yen at 5 p.m. (local
time), up from 143.55-57 yen at 9 a.m., but almost unchanged from
143.70-80 yen late Thursday in New York.
</P>
<P>
Miyazawa said late Thursday night that stock prices and foreign
exchange rates should be left to the market to decide. His remarks
pushed the dollar up by more than 1 yen in New York to as high as
143.88 yen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
