<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Doctor Judges Treatment of Cyclist "Scandalous" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The famous French cancer specialist
and medical ethicist Leon Schwartzenberg Friday judged the
treatment of cyclists in the Tour de France cycling tournament as
"scandalous."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with France 2 television, Schwartzenberg said
that even if people knew that some cyclists had been doped, they
should let them finish the tour before starting a debate on what
one should do about it.
</P>
<P>
"From the moment when all the people knew or claim to know that
these cyclists could be doped, they should give them peace and let
the Tour de France continue and, once it is completed, decide what
one should do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He accused the president of the International Cyclist Union of
"clearing away by taking a vacation in India."
</P>
<P>
"By consequence, very clearly, there has been a scandal and the
scandal unfortunately is shown through the way in which the French
judicial authorities and police have acted, which is not very
shining for our country," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
