<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Industry Picks up in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Tourist Board Chairman
Eliud Mahihu says the tourism industry had substantially
recovered after one year slump.
</P>
<P>
However, campaign efforts to penetrate Germany was "still a
problem," he was quoted by Friday's Daily Nation newspaper as
saying. Germany is the main source of tourists to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"As far as the United Kingdom, Switzerland and French markets
are concerned, things have started to change for the better, but
we are still having problems with Germany," he told the ongoing
12th biennial ambassadors' conference in Mombasa Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the German market was jittery due to the intense
negative publicity the western media had subjected prospective
holiday makers to.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the Kenya Association of Hotel Keepers
and Caterers show that between January and October last year, a
total of 394,880 beds in Kenyan hotels were occupied by Germans.
</P>
<P>
Mahihu said however that the board had launched a major
campaign drive in Europe, where it had placed advertizements in
35 leading travel magazines with a readership of about 45 million
people.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,500 outdoor posters had been placed at approaches
to towns and shopping malls in Switzerland while a similar number
of videos on Kenya had been sent to travels agents in Europe, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mahihu said some of the measures taken to help the industry
recover include educational visits for travel agents and dealing
with the international media on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
The industry went into a free fall last year following the
Likoni clashes and was also affected by the collapsed
infrastructure following the El Nino-induced rains and the
outbreak of water-borne epidemics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Prince Ranariddh Leaves for Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's ousted first-premier
Prince Norodom Ranariddh left here Friday for Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
His trip came after the ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP)
claimed victory in the July 26 election, which Ranariddh regarded
as "unjust and unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
Partial results indicated that the CPP would become the largest
party in the National Assembly, thus having the right to name
Cambodia's next prime minister. The CPP fielded co-premier Hun
Sen, Ranariddh's arch rival, as the candidate for the premiership.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen has said the CPP wants to form a coalition with
Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC party and the opposition Sam Rainsy Party
(SRP).
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, the FUNCINPEC party and the SRP said
they would not take part in the coalition with the CPP or engage
in any negotiations related to the formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
"To speak about power-sharing and the like is highly
inappropriate at this time. Those who threaten to govern outside
the structures of the Constitution... are undermining the
democratic will of the Cambodian people," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The FUNCINPEC party and the SRP rejected the election because
of "fraud" and "irregularities" in the election process.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by Ranariddh and SRP leader Sam Rainsy,
said the two parties would not accept the results of the election
unless "the serious irregularities reported are shown not to have
altered the outcome of the election".
</P>
<P>
The statement called on the neutral observers to "investigate
the evidence and assess the validity of the election results".
</P>
<P>
Earlier, international observers said the election was
"basically free and fair" and could be accepted.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian National Election Committee has set up a special
panel to look into reports of election fraud and intimidation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
