<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shootings on Namibia-Botswana Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Botswana Defense Force (BDF)
troops have shot and killed two Namibians close to the border
between the two countries, Business Day newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Namibian police confirmed Thursday that the anti-poaching unit
of the BDF, which has stationed troops around two disputed
islands in Chobe River in the Caprivi Strip, killed two alleged
Namibian poachers in the Kwando area 10 days ago, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The site of the shootings is in Botswana, about five
kilometers from the Namibian border.
</P>
<P>
News of the killings coincides with the current state visit to
Namibia by Botswana President Festus Mogae, who is scheduled to
discuss several issues, including growing tension between the
countries' troops over the disputed islands.
</P>
<P>
Botswana authorities told Namibian police that Joseph Mukupi
and Lubata Mungowe, both from a village in Caprivi, had been
armed and were shot dead in "retaliatory fire."
</P>
<P>
Two other Namibians reportedly escaped unhurt.
</P>
<P>
The incident is considered a serious blow to Mogae's three-day
visit to Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the BDF deployed troops along its border
with Namibia where the two disputed islands, Kasikili (called
Sedudu in Botswana) and Situngu, are located.
</P>
<P>
The move appeared to be in line with Botswana's initial plans
of erecting camps manned by its troops every 10 kilometers
stretching from the disputed island of Situngu to the border
located near the Mahangu Game Reserve in Botswana territory.
</P>
<P>
Namibian authorities feel that before occupying the islands
Botswana should have directed a request to the Organization of
African Unity, the United Nations or the Southern African
Development Community to mediate.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have subsequently set up a joint technical
committee to discuss the border issue and to demarcate the
stretch on the Chobe River.
</P>
<P>
Following the latest incident, Namibian President Sam Nujoma
was criticized Thursday by the official opposition party, the
Democratic Turnhalle Alliance (DTA), which said his reaction to
the "Trigger-happy" Botswana troops had been lukewarm. DTA Vice
President Katuutire Kaura said Nujoma should take stronger action
to curb the actions of Botswana and preserve stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Kaura suggested that the timing of Mogae's visit to Windhoek
was good because it should encourage Nujoma to take up the issue
with him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kwan Leads Ladies Program in Figure Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Michelle Kwan, world champion in
figure skating, performed almost perfectly tonight in the ladies'
short program of figure skating to excite the audience of 5,580 at
the Goodwill Games in Long Island, New York.
</P>
<P>
"It was so hard to concentrate because the people were cheering
so loud," said Kwan after her performance at the Nassau Veteran
Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
Kwan, gold medalist at the 1997 and 1998 world figure skating
championships, got three 5.8 and four 5.9 points for technical
performance and six 5.9 points and one full 6.0 point for
presentation, topping all the eight skaters from four countries.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old American skater with Chinese origin made twists
and spins in a flying-like dance.
</P>
<P>
Her performance gained a loud applause right from the beginning
to the end.
</P>
<P>
"I know they probably watched Olympics on TV and all the
competitions I've been at over the years and they've watched me
grow," Kwan said on the reaction from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
"I was just there to do it again and I was going out there to
basically concentrate. You are very sure of yourself and you are
confident, said Kwan. "When I started off, I knew I was going to
do it."
</P>
<P>
The short program was part of the event and the final result
will not come out until the long program on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Following Kwan was Russia's Maria Butyrskaya, who finished
third at the world championships and fourth at the Olympics,
overtook her compatriot Irina Slutskaya.
</P>
<P>
The latter, who was the silver medalist at the world figure
skating championships, was fifth because of her fall in a
performance.
</P>
<P>
France's Victoria Volchkova, the world championships fourth
place finisher, ranked third tonight.
</P>
<P>
Before the ladies' program, original dance was held.
</P>
<P>
The standings after the dance maintained the order as in
Wednesday's compulsory dance.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Anjelika Krylova and Oleg Ovsiannikov were still
leading and their teammates, Irina Lobacheva and Ilia Averbukh,
were second.
</P>
<P>
The third on the standings were Elena Grushina and Ruslan
Goncharov from Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
