<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Action Sought Against Drugs Trafficking in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A just-ending top-level
international conference on drug trafficking held here has
recommended measures to curb the escalating problem in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The conference, chaired by Noah arap Too, Director of Criminal
Investigation Department of Kenya, was attended by 84 delegates
from 42 countries of Africa, Europe, Asia, America and Australia,
the Daily Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Interpol, the Organization of African
Unity, the U.N. International Drug Control Program and World
Customs Organization also attended the three-day meeting ending
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting recommended that member states of the United
Nations should be encouraged to establish bilateral and
multilateral agreements on drug law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Another resolution was that postal services personnel be
provided with adequate training to help in detecting drug
offenses and that drug enforcement units improve cooperation with
other relevant services such as immigration and customs.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the anti-narcotics police unit, other state
departments, like the customs and judiciary as well as importers
and distributors of chemicals, should be involved in control of
the drugs, the meeting suggested.
</P>
<P>
The conference also asked more opportunities to be created for
convening operational meetings in order to improve knowledge of
procedures and relationships, both at national and international
levels, between different law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
With strict measures effected in many western countries,
attention is now being focused on Africa and other regions where
there are still loopholes in the anti-drugs campaign, said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
