<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Deports 75,000 Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania deported more than
75,000 illegal immigrants last year, the Minister of Defense and
National Service, Edgar Maokola-Majogo, has said.
</P>
<P>
The illegal immigrants came from Rwanda, Burundi and the
Democratic Republic of Congo, who were causing unrest in the
northwest regions of Kigoma and Kagera, media reports said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Maokola-Majogo, who was presenting his ministry's 1998/99
budget estimates in the central city of Dodoma at the National
Assembly on Thursday, said that the influx of illegal aliens
heightened crimes such as theft, poaching, harassment and murder.
</P>
<P>
He said the escalating banditry incidents created fear and
uncertainties among the local people, forcing the Tanzanian armed
forces to carry out a special operation to maintain law and
order.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, said that Tanzania will continue
co-operating with Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of Congo so
as to maintain peace in the Great Lakes Region.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister also reportedly said that the Tanzania
People's Defense Forces will take part in a military exercise to be
held in South Africa soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
