<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chen Xitong Sentenced to 16 Years Imprisonment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The law court looked into and verified a great amount of
testimony, written documents and other evidence, and heard the
opinions of the public prosecutors, Chen's defence lawyers and
Chen himself.
</P>
<P>
After hearing the testimony, the judges concluded that Chen had
misappropriated 22 gifts, valued at 555,000 yuan, which he had
obtained from official contacts with foreign parties from July
1991 to November 1994 while serving as mayor and Party chief of
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Among these items were eight gold and silver products, six de
luxe watches, four expensive pens, three cameras and one video
camera.
</P>
<P>
According to the appropriate rules and regulations these gifts,
obtained on diplomatic occasions, should have been be handed over
to the state.
</P>
<P>
It was also established that Chen, in pursuit of a corrupt and
decadent life, had instigated and conspired with Wang Baosen,
former Beijing vice-major, to build two luxurious villas in the
Beijing suburbs with public funds for the use and enjoyment of
himself and Wang.
</P>
<P>
From January 1993 to February 1995, Chen frequented the two
villas for extravagant wining, dining and personal entertainment,
the verdict said.
</P>
<P>
The illegally obtained villas and furnishings cost 35.21
million yuan of public funds, management and service fees amounted
to 2.42 million yuan, and his wining and dining there cost 1.05
million yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Foreign Ministry Releases More Files </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and Trade is lifting access restrictions on nearly 5,000
of its files held at the National Archives here.
</P>
<P>
According to a media release issued here Friday by the
ministry, the released files span an 80-year period up to 1970 and
will be freely available to researchers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This release follows the release of 1,700 files last year.
</P>
<P>
The media release said that approximately 12 percent of the
ministry's archived files reviewed since September 1997 remains
under restriction. However this material will continue to be
available to researchers subject to Official Information and
Privacy Act criteria.
</P>
<P>
The files made public over the past year come under 30 subject
headings and cover a diverse range of topics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chen Xitong Sentenced to 16 Years Imprisonment (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Higher People's Court said that as a
state employee, Chen took valuable gifts during contacts with
foreign parties, violating related state regulations.
</P>
<P>
The court said Chen should have turned over these gifts to the
state, but did not, and illegally took the gifts as his own. His
actions, involving extraordinarily huge amounts of money, was
actually graft and must be punished according to law, the court
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who failed to fulfill his duties correctly, incited and
conspired with Wang Baosen to embezzle funds. Their actions were
contrary to the examination and approval procedures set by the
state regarding capital construction projects, the court pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Using this money, they built two luxurious villas and spent
large amounts there without restraint on pleasure-seeking and
wining and dining, causing especially huge losses of public
property and betraying the interests of the state and the
people. His actions are regarded as dereliction of duty and must
be punished in accordance with law, the court said.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 people, including those from various social
circles in the Chinese capital and press people, heard today's
public court verdict. Chen's family members were also present at
the court today.
</P>
<P>
The verdict of the Beijing Municipal Higher People's Court is a
judgment of first instance. According to the country's Criminal
Procedural Law, Chen may appeal to the Supreme People's Court
within 10 days, beginning the day after he received the court
verdict, if he disagrees with the verdict.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
