<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices Plunge at New Zealand's Wool Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Prices plunged at a wool sale
held Thursday in Napier, an east coastal city on North Island of
New Zealand, with 40 percent of the wool sent to auction passed
in, a local newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
At the Napier wool sale, the first of the season, the New
Zealand Wool Group market indicator slumped 48 cents to 408 cents
in a poor start to the new auction season, The Dominion said.
</P>
<P>
The strong wool indicator fell 42 cents to 357 cents, while the
indicator for lambs wool dived 73 cents to 390 cents.
</P>
<P>
There were 1,680 clean tons (14,238 bales) of wool on offer at
Thursday's sale. Compared with the Napier sale on June 25,
crossbred prices for wool of 37 micron were up to 10 percent
cheaper. For all other fiber diameters, they were generally 7.5
percent cheaper.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that before the sale, the Wool Group had reduced
its forecast price for the coming season to 450 cents despite the
drop in the exchange rate for the New Zealand dollar, because of a
deterioration in demand.
</P>
<P>
The next wool sale will be at South Island's Christchurch on
August 5 and 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
