<HEADLINE> 2 U.S. F-14 Fighters Collide in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. Navy fighter planes
collided Thursday evening over the eastern Mediterranean Sea off
Turkey, leaving a pilot dead and another injured, the Anatolia
News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
David Wood, U.S. commander lieutenant colonel of "Tom Cat
Fleet" of the aircraft carrier USS Dwight Eisenbower, said the two
F-14s collided when they were about to land on the carrier, which
was about 108 kilometers off Antalya, a tourist province of
southwestern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The two pilots bailed out from the fighters, but one died and
the other got injured, said the agency. The injured had been taken
by a U.S C-60 type helicopter to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Wood, who accompanied the pilot to a hospital of the Medical
Faculty of the Mediterranean University for treatment, said "one
fighter plane succeeded in landing on the carrier and the other
crashed into the sea."
</P>
<P>
The carrier, with 6,054 personnel including 594 officers, will
stay at Antalya Port from 31 July to 6 August.
</P>
<P>
The carrier has visited Antalya Port several times before.
</P>
</TEXT>
