<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Birds Destroy Wheat in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Millions of the destructive
quelea birds are invading wheat farms in Narok, Nakuru and Uasin
Gishu districts, Rift Valley Province of Kenya, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rift Valley Provincial Director of Agriculture K.K.
Chepsaigutt was quoted as saying that some farmers had lost as
much as 20 per cent of their crop to the birds.
</P>
<P>
The report said it was estimated that the size of the quelea
colonies had about five million birds.
</P>
<P>
Teams from the Kenyan Ministry of Agriculture were fighting
against the birds daily, using motorized ground chemical sprayers
and aeroplanes for spraying, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Nakuru District Agricultural Officer J. Muchoki said that one
flock of quelea birds at Ngata area near Nakuru town had about a
million birds. Another at Menengai hill had 100,000 birds while
another roost at Ngongongeri farm belonging to Egerton University
had about 500,000 birds.
</P>
<P>
A flock of about 200,000 birds had been spotted at Gicheha
farm and another comprising 40,000 birds had been roosting at
Mosonik farm.
</P>
<P>
Muchoki said that the birds had increased significantly
because of the plenteous grass.
</P>
<P>
Rift Valley Province is the main producer of grain in the
country but the area under the crop has dropped drastically
during the last two decades due to land sub-division, according
to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
