<HEADLINE> Kwan Steals Spotlight at Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Michelle Kwan, world figure
skating champion in 1996 and 1998, produced a flawless performance
to bring the local crowd to their standing ovation here Thursday
in the women's short program at the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
The American beamed after ranking first with a big margin,
saying: "I felt remarkably good. It was hard to concentrate
because the people were cheering so loud. I just enjoyed myself,
let loose, and let it go."
</P>
<P>
The delicate-looking Kwan said it was fun to be able to change
tempo right in the short program. "I could be dramatic. I could be
soft. I could be all the emotions at once."
</P>
<P>
She had a fall when she made a triple lutz during the warm up,
but she finished the action perfect in the race.
</P>
<P>
"It is just a warm-up and anything I do in the warm up doesn't
really matter. The warm-up is just to clean your mind and start
from scratch again. If you land a triple axel in warm up, it
doesn't matter, you still have to do it in the program," said Kwan.
</P>
<P>
A cheering crowd backed up Kwan whenever she appeared on the
ice.
</P>
<P>
"I know they probably watched the Olympics on TV, and all the
competitions I've been at over the years and they've watched me
grow," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
