<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria, Diarrhea Break out in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaria, viral fever and diarrhea
have broken out in Bangladesh's northeastern district, with 200
people being attacked in the past month.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 people have suffered from viral fever and 500 from
diarrhea in the malaria-prone district of Sunamganj, 188
kilometers northeast of here, The Bangladesh Observer daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The symptoms of the fever are high temperature, muscular pain
and headache, according to physicians.
</P>
<P>
Many people die of malaria every year in the district, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
In order to control the spread of the diseases, the health
department and the local government have already distributed over
4,700 mosquito-nets among the people in the district. At the same
time health workers have been working round the clock in the
malaria-affected areas.
</P>
<P>
However, the report pointed out that no other effective steps
have been taken to combat viral fever and diarrhea due to the lack
of medicine and medical facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chen Xitong Sentenced to 16 Years Imprisonment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Municipal Higher
People's Court this morning sentenced Chen Xitong, former
secretary of the Beijing Municipal Committee of the Communist
Party of China, to 16 years imprisonment on charges of corruption
and dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
The sentence was pronounced in a public court session here
today. The verdict said Chen was sentenced to 13 years
imprisonment on the charge of corruption and to four years
on the charge of dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
All together, Chen will serve 16 years in prison, according to
the the verdict, which added that the bribes Chen accepted shall
be confiscated and turned over to the State Treasury.
</P>
<P>
Chen was arrested on February 27, 1998 by authority of the
Beijing People's Procuratorate on suspicion of corruption and
dereliction of duty. The Beijing People's Procuratorate initiated
legal proceedings on these charges against Chen on June 5 this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Higher People's Court said it conducted a
non-public trial on July 20 in accordance with the first clause of
Article 152 of the Chinese Criminal Procedural Law, which states
that trials involving state secrets or individual privacy shall
not be open to the public.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing People's Procuratorate served as the prosecutor for
this case, and Chen was defended by his lawyer Wang Yaoting of the
Beijing Fengshi Law Firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
