<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0530 GMT, July 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The 15-nation European Union registered a
1.3-percent increase in industrial production between February and
April this year, Eurostat reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the European
communities said that the 11-country euro zone also posted an
industrial production increase of 1.3 percent. (EU-Production)
</P>
<P>
-- -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- A total of 29.5 percent of the labor force in
South Africa are unemployed, Labor Minister Shepherd Mdladlana
quoted a survey by the Central Statistical Services as saying
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The figure of unemployment included those who are not actively
looking for work, Mdladlana said in a written reply to a
parliamentary question from the opposition National Party.
(SAfrica-Unemployed Figure)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German industrial group Daimler-Benz Thursday announced
in Frankfurt that its profits doubled to a record high of some 3.8
billion marks (2.1 billion U.S. dollars) in the first half from
the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Group turnover surged 21 percent to 67.7 billion marks (38.2
billion dollars), boosting net profits to two billion marks (1.1
billion dollars) from one billion marks (565 million dollars), the
level a year before. (Germany-Daimler-Profits)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The annual inflation rate for the 11 countries
joining the single currency system remained stable at 1.4 percent
on the average, Eurostat reported Thursday. (EU-Euro
Countries-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Foreign banks in South Africa have believed
that there are too many overseas financial institutions in the
country to make enough business, local daily Business Day quoted a
survey by Canadian academic Brian Metcalfe as reporting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"More than 75 foreign banks have a presence in the South
African market, but 78 percent of those interviewed are calling
the market overbanked, with not enough business for everyone,"
said Tom Winterboer, who was involved in doing the survey.
(SAfrica-Foreign Banks)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has threatened to cut its trade with some
European countries if the European Union (EU) imposes anti-dumping
duties on Egyptian unbleached cotton exports, the Egyptian Gazette
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The EU's executive body is believed to have proposed
anti-dumping duties averaging 12 percent on imports of unbleached
cotton fabric from some countries including Egypt, India,
Indonesia and Pakistan, accusing them of unfairly selling their
products in Europe. (Egypt-EU-Cotton)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- The Vietnamese government has decided to postpone 27
national and regional projects which were funded from the state
budget, Vietnam News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The postponement is part of a government decision to reduce
spending in anticipation of an economic downturn caused by the
regional crisis, said the report. (Vietnam-Economy)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- New Zealand's beef cattle numbers on July 1,
1998 were down 8 percent to 4.42 million, compared with the
figure a year earlier, an official media release
said here Thursday. (New Zealand-Livestock Numbers)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's unemployment rate in June reached a record
high since World War Two of 4.3 percent, the Management and
Coordination Agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The jump surpassed the previous high of 4.1 percent set in both
April and May. The number of unemployed has risen by 24 percent
since 1997, going up by 550,000 to 2.84 million, said the agency.
(Japan-Unemployment)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States and South Korea Thursday signed
a new bilateral agreement, reopening the U.S. Overseas Private
Investment Corporation (OPIC) program to invest in the crisis-hit
country.
</P>
<P>
The agreement means OPIC can offer insurance and other types of
financial support to U.S. companies that want to do business in
South Korea. (US-S.Korea-Investment) 
</P>
</TEXT>
