<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Begins Investigating Election Fraud in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A special commission set up
Thursday by Cambodian National Election Committee (NEC) has begun
to look into reports of election fraud and complaints made by some
political parties, NEC announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Election Results Control Commission consisting of four
members of the NEC is chaired by Kassie Neou, vice chairman of NEC.
</P>
<P>
The mission of the commission is to respond to any complaints
concerning election results and take necessary corrective actions,
including random checking, investigation, and recounting ballots.
</P>
<P>
So far, the commission has received 50 complaints from
political parties and has begun to look into them, Kassie Neon
said.
</P>
<P>
Kassie Neon asked the political parties with complaints to
submit their reports before next Tuesday, the deadline for appeals
against the initial results to be released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Demands for new elections in some disputed areas will be
considered if the complaints are justified," he said.
</P>
<P>
More than twelve small parties joined Funcinpec and Sam Rainsy
Party in protesting alleged irregularities in the elections.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that in some areas where major irregularities
occurred, the elections should be reorganized and carried out with
proper procedure and observation.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-nine political parties took part in the National
Assembly election held on July 26. The ruling Cambodian People's
Party led by Second Prime Minister Hun Sen appears to be the
winner with more than half of five million votes counted.
</P>
<P>
The final results of the election is expected to be announced
on mid-August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
