<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif, who is in Colombo for a summit of South Asian leaders,
said the outcome of his talks with Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee was "zero," the Island newspaper reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the local newspaper, Sharif said he told
his Indian counterpart that Pakistan wanted the dialogue between
the two countries to be resumed just as much India wanted them to
be resumed.
</P>
<P>
At their talks here on Wednesday on the sidelines of the South
Asian leaders' summit, Sharif and Vajpayee agreed to resume the
dialogue between the two arch-rivals in the region. And the two
countries' foreign secretaries have been asked to hold talks to
work out the "modalities" for the resumption of the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"So let us resolve the issue of Kashmir in a serious and
substantive manner so that we would be able to make progress,"
Sharif was quoted as telling Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
However, the Indian prime minister was not willing to focus on
Kashmir prominently or wanted Kashmir to figure prominently in a
joint communique, according to Sharif.
</P>
<P>
"If that was the position, what is the point in having these
talks because Kashmir was the root cause of all the conflicts
between India and Pakistan. We did not want to hold talks for the
sake of talks but for the talks to succeed," the Pakistan prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan have fought three wars since their
independence from Britain in 1947, two of them over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
On May 11 and 13 this year, India carried out nuclear tests,
and late in that month, Pakistan also conducted nuclear tests in a
tit-for-tat manner, prompting fears of a nuclear arms race in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he would describe the outcome of his talks as a
"stalemate," Sharif said: "Yes, it is a stalemate. We are not here
to waste each others' time."
</P>
<P>
But he added that he and Vajpayee did exchange views on matters
concerning the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also said that his visit to Colombo for the summit of
the seven-member South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC) was a success, particularly because he had been able to
make his proposal on peace and security for South Asia in his
address to the opening of the three-day gathering on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Colombo SAARC summit ends on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
