<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEBI Plans to Curb on Short Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Securities and Exchange
Board of India (SEBI) is considering several measures to
streamline the stock markets in the country including a possible
ban on short sales on the downtick and disallowing 'naked' short
sales-or short sales of a scrip without actual possession of even
a single share, official sources said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The market watchdog is also expected to lay down specific
parameters for the inclusion of stocks in the carry-forward list,
after considering the opinions of the stock exchanges in the
matter.
</P>
<P>
Since most of the these measures are crucial policy decisions,
the SEBI is expected to take them up before a final verdict is
given, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The issues relating to short sales are being seen as crucial
for the safety of the market, since the regulator is keen on
clamping down on misuse of the carry-forward mechanism.
</P>
<P>
SEBI officials said that the inherent inadequacies of the
present system make it possible for a short seller to earn money
despite not having any shares. With stocklending now a reality, it
is felt that a measure where the short seller is made to borrow
the stocks would be in order. Naked short sales are completely
banned in developed markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Decides not to Seek Outside Aid for Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government in
principle has decided not to seek financial aid from abroad to
provide relief and succor to the victims of current flood.
</P>
<P>
The government had sufficient stock of food to feed the
flood-affected people, a media report Friday quoted an official as
saying here Thursday. "We'll try to manage the present situation
with internal resources, " he added.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina had instructed an emergency stock
of 1.2 million tons of grains to face the flood and post-flood
situation in the country, the official stated.
</P>
<P>
The government had now one million tons of rice in its own
stock and it was procuring another 0.2 million tons, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Ministry of Finance had allocated 15 million taka
(0.319 million U.S. dollars) apart from budget allocation for cash
relief.
</P>
<P>
Under the government supervision, the departments concerned had
already distributed 10.67 million taka (0.23 million dollars) and
26,112 tons of grains to the flood victims in the 37 flood-hit
districts.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) had been requested to send
some five million water-purifying tablets to ensure pure drinking
water for the marooned people and keep safe from the water-borne
diseases in the aftermath of flood, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Since early this month, heavy rains have downpoured in this
South Asian country, and so far, over 17.5 million people living
in the 37 districts out of the total of 64 have been affected by
flood, with death toll rising to 188 as of Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Over 5,000 kilometers of roads, 1,722 kilometers of embankments
and 2,215 bridges and culverts damaged, and about 200,000 houses
and nearly 200,000 hectares of standing crops washed away by the
flood.
</P>
<P>
Diarrhea, dysentery and other flood-borne diseases have broken
out in some flood-hit districts as acute crisis of drinking water
was prevailing there, reports said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the flood situation has improved slowly, with the
situation having returned normal in 11 of the 37 flood-hit
districts and improved in nine districts, according to officials
of the Flood Forecasting and Warning Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0217 </DOCNO>
