<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adds Billions to Build Highways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China plans to increase this
year's highway construction allocations by 20 billion yuan (2.4
billion U.S. dollars) to 180 billion yuan as part of an effort to
bolster domestic demand, according to sources from the Ministry of
Communications.
</P>
<P>
Minister Huang Zhendong said the Ministry of Finance
allocations and banks loans will account for the bulk of funding
which will be used to support 172 highway construction projects
during 1998. The projects will increase the nation's highway
network by 17,736 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
China increased the original 120 billion yuan in budgeted
highway construction funds to 160 billion yuan in early March.
</P>
<P>
Increased funding for 1998 will support the construction of
highways which will expand the existing highway network by 33,000
km, including expressways totaling 1,560 kilometers, according to
the the minister.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the 60 billion yuan in added investment is
expected to account for 0.31 percent of the country's targeted
eight percent growth in gross domestic product.  
</P>
</TEXT>
