<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Jobless Rate Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Japan's unemployment rate in June
reached a record high since World War Two of 4.3 percent, the
Management and Coordination Agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The jump surpassed the previous high of 4.1 percent set in both
April and May. The number of unemployed has risen by 24 percent
since 1997, going up by 550,000 to 2.84 million, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate was a high for both men and women, with the
male jobless rate matching the 4.3 percent in May and the female
jobless rate breaking the previous record of 4.0 percent in April
to hit 4.2 percent, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the number of unemployed men shot up 28 percent
to 1.69 million, while that of unemployed women jumped 18.6
percent to 1.15 million.
</P>
<P>
"The situation for employment has become more severe," an
agency official said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Labor Ministry said in a separate report that the
ratio of job offers to job seekers dropped to 0.51 in June from
0.53 in May. This meant there were only 51 job offers for every
100 people looking for work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
