<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Evaluate Alternative Health-Care Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar health authorities is
holding a seminar here to evaluate the country's alternative
health-care financing for effective disease control and promotion
of public health-care services.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar, which began Thursday, is sponsored by the
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Minister of Health Major-General Ket Sein, Friday's
official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar said health-care
should not depend solely on the private sector, calling for saving
harmonious efforts between the government and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that although the government is
increasing health expenditure, it has not reached the satisfactory
level yet due to rising of prices in medicines and medical
equipment, noting that it is difficult for the state to bear all
the national health expenditures alone due to increase in breaking
out of infectious and non-infectious diseases which is a problem
in developing nations including Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for implementing cost-sharing health
project, a contribution to the income, calling for attending to
the poor who are not able to reach the cost-sharing health system
to enjoy proper health-care.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the health personnel to strive for promotion of
public health standard and saving people's lives.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has worked out a five-year national health plan for
1996-2001 which includes six broad programs and 50 detailed
projects.
</P>
<P>
Attending the seminar are ministers from various ministries,
officials of some local non-governmental organizations as well as
representatives of the World Health Organization and the United
Nations Development Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
