<HEADLINE> Milosevic Reaffirms Political Settlement for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic reaffirmed on Thursday that the Kosovo crisis must be
solved by political means, the state news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
The issue must be solved through political means, and talks
between the Serbian authorities and Kosovo political parties must
be resumed, Milosevic told a meeting with a European Union team
visiting the region.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic emphasized that the international community should
condemn terrorist activities in Kosovo, and cut off all sources of
funds to the "terrorists".
</P>
<P>
Serbia and the Yugoslav Federation are determined to curb any
violence that poses threats to the peace, freedom and the equality
of all ethnic groups in Kosovo, warned Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
The EU delegation, formed with diplomats from Austria, Britain
and Germany, arrived in this region on Tuesday, in a bid to
mediate a settlement to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting with Milosevic, the delegation on Wednesday
visited the central and western towns of Malisevo and Kijevo, both
scenes of recent fighting.
</P>
<P>
The delegation also had talks with ethnic Albanian leaders in
Pristina, capital of the rebel province Kosovo, urging them to
unite for talks with Belgrade over the future of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out in Kosovo in late February when Serbian
forces launched a crackdown on separatists in the southern Serbian
province, which is 90 percent ethnic Albanian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
