<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Postulate Plateau Affects Climate Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The upheaval of the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau is quite likely an extremely important factor contributing
to the ongoing transition to a colder global climate, according to
scientists attending an international symposium on the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau here.
</P>
<P>
Most Chinese and foreign geologists and meteorologists agree
with views expressed during the recent symposium.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xiaodong, a researcher at the Institute of Plasma Physics,
explained that global warming over the past two years has resulted
from the green house effect and the El Nino phenomenon. However,
he also pointed out that the world has witnessed the tendency for
a colder climate over the past 60 million years.
</P>
<P>
Liu said scientists studying the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau have
observed that the earth has experienced three distinct periods of
colder climates.
</P>
<P>
The first period occurred some 36 million years ago, the
second around 15 million years, and the third within the past 2-3
million years. The three periods coincided with the three periods
of upheavals on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Scientists postulated that the plateau, an area covering 2.5
million sq.km., experienced serious denudation during the
upheaval periods.
</P>
<P>
The fact that denudation siphoned vast amounts of carbon
dioxide and reduced the atmosphere's effectiveness in absorbing
heat from sunshine resulting in a colder global climate.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the symposium agreed that research concerning
the relationship between climate changes and upheavals on the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau will be extremely important for forecasting
future global climate patterns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0241 </DOCNO>
