<HEADLINE> Hubei Closely Monitors Dike Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Seemingly endless rainfall has
intensified threats to dikes in many areas along the Yangtze
River in central China's Hubei Province, according to a local
flood control official.
</P>
<P>
Teams monitoring Hubei's dikes reported 164 cave-ins on
Monday, 165 on Tuesday and 147 on Wednesday, with a five- to
eight-fold increase in reports over the previous 20-day
period. Reports from heavily flooded areas indicate even more
serious situations.
</P>
<P>
The water level in the downstream city of Shashi City has
remained above flood stage for some 20-odd days. Reports through
July 30 indicated dangerous situations in more than 1,700 places
related to cave-ins, eroding dikes and cracks
</P>
<P>
The provincial flood control headquarters has called on all
armymen and civilians to maintain a constant vigil to monitor the
flood status and deal with dangerous situations in order to ensure
the integrity of Yangtze River dikes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
