<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Minister Leaves for Border Talks With Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Public Security
Minister Juan Rafael Lizano left here Thursday for Nicaragua to
discuss border disputes with Nicaraguan officials.
</P>
<P>
His visit came one week after a conflict broke out on a border
river between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
After the conflict, Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman said
sovereignty of the river is not negotiable, and it is defended
with weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican security minister is expected to meet with his
Nicaraguan counterpart, Jaime Cuadra.
</P>
<P>
He said before leaving for Nicaragua that his country will not
back down from what it considers its right to unencumbered
navigation on the border river.
</P>
<P>
Under treaties in force, the river is under Nicaragua's
sovereignty, but Costa Rica has a right to free navigation.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica believed that the transit of their police on the
river is assured by the treaty, but Nicaragua insisted that armed
personnel could not navigate on the river.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua also believed its sovereignty over the river gave its
authorization to supervise the transit of Costa Rican authorities.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican foreign ministry sources here said that Lizano's
visit might pave way for another meeting between the two foreign
ministers or even the two presidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
