<HEADLINE> Economic News in Brief from Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's imports in the first four months this
year totaled 3.8 billion U.S. dollars, up 18.2 percent from the
same period of 1997, said the country's Statistics and Information
Central Office.
</P>
<P>
The United States took the lion's share of 44.1 percent of
Venezuela's total imports, followed by Colombia with 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Electrical equipment, chemicals and common metals were the
major imports.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Lasmo, a British independent oil company,
sold its operations in Colombia to a subsidiary of Petrobras, the
Brazilian state-run oil company, for 151 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Braspetro Oil Services subsidiary of Petrobras, which is
interested in expanding its business in South America, will
initially pay Lasmo 75 percent of the price of the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
The British company's assets in Colombia are worth 46 million
pounds (77.9 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's coffee exports in the first half of
this year reached 256.15 million dollars, up 14.06 percent from
the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is one of the most important agricultural products in
the country's exports, and represented 29.4 percent of the total
exports of agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The United States embassy in Uruguay destroyed a
total of 448,000 fake dollars on July 30.
</P>
<P>
The counterfeit money was seized last year at Solymar beach
when a sailor saw a man abandon a bag, containing half a million
dollars in counterfeit bills and metal plates to print the bills.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The earnings of Nicaragua's sea food product exports
in the first six months this year were 35 million dollars more
than that in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The fishing sector kept its second place as the country's
generator of hard currency from exports, increasing its earning by
0.11 percent.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Economy and Development Ministry said this
increase could have been higher had "El Nino" not caused so much
damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
