<HEADLINE> Round UP: U.N., Taliban to strive for Resolving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia and
officials of the U.N. Afghanistan mission will meet in Kabul
Saturday to find ways as to how dozens of international relief
agencies which left Kabul last week are enabled to revive their
suspended operations.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports from Kabul said that the Taliban militia have
agreed to meet the U.N. officials after repeated efforts by the
U.N. and other international donors.
</P>
<P>
Until now the Taliban are firmed not to budge from its stance
and lift the relocation order it had earlier served on these
relief agencies which led to closure of their offices in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Peshawar-based Afghan NGOs
Coordination Bureau (ANCB) has offered its mediation between the
Taliban and foreign relief agencies within its capacity to resolve
the misunderstanding between the concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
In an appeal issued in Peshawar by ANCB, Chairman Qamaruddin
Jabarkhel said "ANCB believes if the prerequisite of international
guidelines and Islamic and cultural values of Afghanistan
respected by the NGOs and the Taliban authority provides proper
facilities, it will be possible to achieve the ultimate goal of
serving the Afghan public."
</P>
<P>
"The international humanitarian goals while making decisions
should strive to resolve their conflicts with the Taliban through
negotiations and consider the welfare of Afghans in general and
the residents of Kabul in particular," he said.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, Agency Coordination Body for
Afghan Relief (ACBAR) held its general body meeting in Peshawar
Tuesday and reviewed the situation arising out of the policy
adopted by the Taliban administration towards foreign aid
organizations and aid workers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed developments in the light of fresh
initiative by UN and ICRC urging Islamic Taliban militia to lift
relocation order served on international relief agencies earlier
this month, leading to closure of offices and suspension of
operations by dozens of 30 international relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no specific agenda except that ACBAR reviewed
the latest developments in Kabul and response of the Taliban
militia to UN initiative to help restore relief operations in
war-riddled Afghanistan," a spokesman for ACBAR said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that it was a close door meeting attended by
all the ACBAR members. After U.N. agencies, a CBAR based in
Peshawar, capital of Pakistan's North West Frontier Province, is
the largest coordinating body with 72 members including Afghan
organizations coordinating international relief operations in
war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Qari Din Mohammad, a senior Taliban official for planning, said
in an interview with the local press last week that the Taliban
was willing to negotiate with the aid bodies but it will not
change its stand.
</P>
<P>
He said that those left the Afghan capital city were welcome to
return provided they accept the terms set out by the Taliban .
</P>
<P>
More than 30 international relief agencies closed their offices
and suspended operation last Tuesday when they refused to comply
the order by the Taliban militia served on them to relocate their
offices at polytechnic institute Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Except U.N., ICRC mission and international aid mission, aid
workers of all the remaining agencies have left Kabul and reached
Pakistan waiting for settlement of the core issue of relocation of
their offices between the Taliban and international donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
