<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Raise Environmental Protection Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Environmental Protection Bureau
of the Tibet Autonomous Region in southwest China has recently
received more than 20 letters from residents of Lhasa, capital of
the Autonomous Region, complaining about the ever-increasing dust
and garbage pollution in their lives.
</P>
<P>
There are five cement plants around Lhasa, and one of them is a
pillar industry of the Autonomous Region. The environmental
protection bureau is already consulting with the plant to invest
more than three million yuan (about 370,000 U.S.dollars) in dust
pollution treatment, said Losang, director of the environmental
protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous regional government held a conference on
environmental protection in June, which concluded that "protecting
the environment is essentially protecting productivity, and the
autonomous region must not achieve progress at the expense of its
environment."
</P>
<P>
Concrete measures were worked out at the conference to allocate
more funds for environmental protection, improve environmental
monitoring systems, enhance people's environmental protection
awareness, and improve the capital's garbage treatment
capabilities and other public facilities.
</P>
<P>
The general environmental quality of the Autonomous Region is
quite good, as it is one enormous land left almost untouched in
China, he said, adding that economic and population growth are
putting pressure on the land.
</P>
<P>
"Tibet Daily", the leading newspaper of the region, recently
published a report calling for strengthened protection for a
600-hectare stretch of wet grasslands in northern suburban
Lhasa. The call received a quick response, with the city's mayor
inspecting the region immediately and working out specific
protection measures.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen nature reserves, covering a total area of 325,000
square kilometers, have been established in Tibet, and poaching
activities are frequently stopped by local residents, whose
environmental protection awareness has heightened remarkably,
Losang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
