<HEADLINE> China on Extension of Mandate of U.N. Mission in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The key questions now were
the serious differences that persisted between the government of
Georgia and athe Abkhaz leadership with regard to the future
political status of Abkhaz, China stressed here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting of the Security Council of the United
Nations which adopted a resolution to extend the mandate of the
U.N. mission in the country, Qin Huasun, Chinese ambassador to the
United Nations, said that only when both sides had demonstrated
their political will to solve their differences, would the efforts
of the international community play a role.
</P>
<P>
The final settlement of the question depended on the people
themselves, he added.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the recent high-level meeting between the two sides
was welcome, and he awaited the direct contacts between the
Georgian president and the Abkhaz leader at an early date which
would be the first step to confidence-building between the two
sides and would mark a beginning towards solving the current
problems.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the United Nations mission in Georgia always
maintained excellent relationships with both sides, and it was
disturbing that the mission's security was threatened by the
instability in the country.
</P>
<P>
Qin said China condemned the terrorist attacks and believed
that the two parties would honor their promises to safeguard
international personnel. 
</P>
