<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Woos Support for Sierra Leone Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Thursday called for international support for Sierra Leone's
peace-building efforts as it is a test whether Africa can heel the
conflict wounds.
</P>
<P>
Opening the U.N. Special Conference on Sierra Leone, Annan said
Sierra Leone President Albaji Ahmad Tejan Kabbah has taken a
number of steps to combat the effects of nine months of misrule by
the military junta since he was restored to office in March.
</P>
<P>
The West African country has also sought to lay a new and
lasting foundation for national reconciliation, reconstruction and
rehabilitation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the junta and rebel remnants to lay down their
arms without further delay as there have been continuing attacks
against the government and civilians.
</P>
<P>
Since March 500 victims of mutilations including amputations
have occurred with more people losing their lives or remaining in
the bush in horror, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the peace-building initiatives by Kabbah's
government and international bodies which recognize that "to
ensure lasting gains, the long-term roots of conflict, especially
poverty, must be addressed."
</P>
<P>
"This is why I convened this Special Conference -- to focus
international attention on th situation and to ensure that we
attack the problems with a collective unity of purpose," the
secretary-general noted.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah, elected to office in 1996, was toppled by the military
junta in May 1997. The Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) took over Freetown from the junta in February 1998 and
Kabbah returned to office eventually.
</P>
<P>
Annan called the one-day meeting in consultation with the
government of Sierra Leone and the ECOWAS, focusing on a
disarmament and demobilization plan for former combatants and
other peace-building measures in the country.
</P>
<P>
The peace-keeping and related activities of the ECOMAS,
including its need for financial and other support to alleviate
the manpower and logistical constraints, are on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The conference brings together members of the ECOWAS, the
European Union, the U.N. Security Council and a number of other
U.N. member states, the Organization of African Unity, the
Organization of the Islamic Conference, the Commonwealth and the
Bretton Woods Institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Decides to Extend Mandate of UNOMIG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of the
United Nations Thursday decided to extend the mandate of the
United Nations Mission in Georgia for a further period of six
months until January 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution unanimously adopted, the Security Council
expressed its concern over the resumption of hostilities which
took place in May 1998 and called upon the the government of
Georgia and the Abkhaz side to observe strictly the Moscow
Agreement signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The council also expressed its concern over the significant
outflow of refugees resulting from the recent hostilities, and
reaffirmed the right of all refugees and displaced persons to
return to their homes in secure conditions in accordance with
international law.
</P>
<P>
The council called on the two sides to fulfill their
obligations in this regard, and demanded in particular that the
Abkhaz side allow the unconditional and immediate return of all
persons displaced since the resumption of hostilities in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Security council urged the parties to display without delay
the necessary political will to achieve substantial results on the
key issues of the negotiations, with full respect for the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Georgia, within the
framework of the United Nations-led peace process and through
direct dialogue, and to cooperate fully with the efforts made by
the U.N. secretary-general and his special representative.
</P>
<P>
The council welcomed the meeting of the parties held in Geneva
on July 23-35, 1998 and called upon them to continue and increase
their active engagement in this process initiated by the U.N.
secretary-general aimed at achieving a comprehensive political
settlement.
</P>
<P>
It condemned the acts of violence against the personnel of the
UNOMIG, and demanded that the parties, in particular the Georgian
authorities, take determined measures to put a stop to such acts
which subvert the peace process in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
