<HEADLINE> U.S. to Provide Food Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States will soon
send 500,000 tons of wheat worth 62.5 million U.S. dollars to
Indonesia to help overcome difficulties caused by its collapsed
economy, a senior U.S. official said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brian Atwood, administrator of the Agency for International
Development, told a news conference that Indonesia is too
important to go without outside help during the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Beyond the 500,000 tons of wheat, Washington is ready to
provide up to one million more tons for Indonesia, Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States made the decision to assist
Indonesia because its government had promised to hold democratic
elections next year.
</P>
<P>
The assistance is part of a 300 million U.S. dollar pledge the
United States made at an international donors conference in Paris.
The donors pledged 7.9 billion U.S. dollars in new disbursements
by March 31, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
