<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Set up Regional Telecom Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) plans to invest 300 million U.S. Dollars
to set up a regional telecommunication network.
</P>
<P>
Aaccording to a COMESA document issued Thursday in Mombasa, a
port city in Kenya, the network, which will be known as the
Common Market Telecommunication (COMTEL) company, is expected to
help expand trade within the region.
</P>
<P>
The document was presented during the annual Kenyan
ambassadors' meeting in the Indian Ocean port of Mombasa, said a
report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
This was the result of a study on inter-connectivity and
tariff harmonization of telecommunication network undertaken by
Telia Swedtel AB for COMESA with financing from the African
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is planned to be implemented in five years,
is expected to improve the standard of services to be offered to
360 million customers as low tariffs would make it possible for
increased telecommunication traffic.
</P>
<P>
Among the states involved are Angola, Botswana, Burundi,
Comoros, Djibouti, Egypt, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Lesotho,
Malawi, Madagascar, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Rwanda,
Seychelles, Somalia, South Africa, Sudan, Swaziland, Tanzania,
Uganda, Democratic Republic of Congo, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The Mombasa meeting also endorsed Thursday that the project
will have representation of national telecommunications
operators.
</P>
<P>
"A reliable and efficient telecommunication network in the
COMESA region has long been identified as a key factor in
facilitating the region's economic integration," said the
document.
</P>
<P>
The existing telecommunication infrastructure in most
countries is said to be far below the desired standards.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said the project has already received support
from the third summit of the COMESA in Kinshasa held on June 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
