<HEADLINE> U.S. Resumes Investment Program to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States and South
Korea Thursday signed a new bilateral agreement, reopening the
U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) program to
invest in the crisis-hit country.
</P>
<P>
The agreement means OPIC can offer insurance and other types of
financial support to U.S. companies that want to do business in
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
OPIC suspended the program with South Korea in 1991 due to
concerns about labor rights. But the White House said recently
that conditions had since improved. But it seems business groups
have played a crucial role by throwing heavy pressure on
Washington to end the ban on the OPIC program.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, who attended
the signing ceremony, said the worst of South Korea's financial
crisis appeared to be over.
</P>
<P>
"The hemorrhaging has been staunched.... I believe we have seen
very important progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Summers warned challenges still remained, "particularly in
the financial sector, particularly in the structural area."
</P>
</TEXT>
