<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling May Weaken: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
said Thursday that the upward trend of the Kenyan Shilling
against hard currencies is expected to change in the second half
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Shilling's appreciation from 70 to 59 Shillings against one
U.S. Dollar within a year is due to low demand for foreign
exchange by importers and high inflows from investors who cash in
on the high yields on Treasury bills, said CBK.
</P>
<P>
However, CBK Governor Micah Cheserem said the Shilling may
become weakening as the government implements the belt-tightening
measures announced in the budget for the 1998/99 year (July/June).
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement that the expected recovery will result
in greater demand for foreign exchange which in turn will exert
a downward pressure on the Shilling's exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
A tighter management of government revenues and expenditures
would result in a reduced borrowing by the government from the
banking sector, leading to "more downward pressure on the
exchange rate," the governor said.
</P>
<P>
However, Cheserem cautioned that the Kenyan market tends to
over-react when the local currency is either depreciating or
appreciating.
</P>
<P>
CBK will continue with its strategy of allowing the
Shilling's exchange rate to be determined by market forces, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The target, he added, is to achieve a Shilling exchange rate
that is relatively stable and competitive.
</P>
<P>
However, he said CBK will stand ready to intervene in the
market to smooth out any fluctuations in the exchange rate
occasioned by non-economic sentiments which are not of a
permanent nature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Names Film Star Michael Douglas as Its Messager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations on
Thursday named film star Michael Douglas of the United States as
its messenger of peace for his campaign for nuclear disarmament,
the control of small arms and payment of the huge U.S. debt to
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Michael Douglas said "I hope to use
the entertainment communications ability we have around the
world to talk a little less about movies and hopefully a lot
more about some of the issues pertaining to the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
"This probably means as much to me as any of the two Oscars
that I got," he said.
</P>
<P>
Douglas said he considered nuclear proliferation a human
right issue, the right not to fear countries which have nuclear
problems.
</P>
<P>
He said the spread of small arms was particularly prevalent
in Albania, where the United Nations is attempting to collect
illicit weapons held by civilians, and proliferation of small
arms was killing people around the world in a growing multitude
of civil conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Douglas won his first Academy award in 1975 for producing
"One flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest," which won five awards
including best picture. He received a best actor Oscar in 1987
for his role as Gordon Gekko in "Wall Street".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
