<DOCNO> XIE19980731.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two U.S. Navy F-14s Collide Over Mediterranean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. Navy F-14 fighters
collided Thursday over the eastern Mediterranean Sea with an
aviator killed, said the Navy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The two jets from the aircraft carrier USS Dwight Eisenhower
collided at 6:11 p.m. local time when the carrier was about 150
miles southwest of western Turkey, said a Navy spokesman, Cmdr.
Brian Cullin.
</P>
<P>
One of the fighters crashed into the sea and its two crew
members ejected but one was killed, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The carrier Eisenhower had been in the Mediterranean for just
over a month and is scheduled to remain in the region through
October.
</P>
<P>
The planes, which are from the VF-103 squadron embarked on the
Eisenhower, were involved in "routine flight."
</P>
<P>
Only 10 of the warplanes are on the carrier. F-14s provide
protection to the carrier battle group by conducting routine daily
air patrols.
</P>
<P>
The Navy said that the reason for the collision is under
investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
